WEBVTT

1
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:08,440
[pensive piano music playing]

2
00:00:10,280 --> 00:00:12,160
[water splashing]

3
00:00:12,240 --> 00:00:14,080
[woman] Three, two,

4
00:00:14,160 --> 00:00:15,720
one, and go!

5
00:00:18,680 --> 00:00:19,680
[whistle blowing]

6
00:00:31,160 --> 00:00:32,400
I win.

7
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:33,840
Oh, come on, again, please.

8
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:35,120
[chuckling]

9
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:36,640
Okay.

10
00:00:37,160 --> 00:00:39,120
I'm totally gonna win this time.

11
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:41,960
[sighs happily]

12
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:43,520
[sinister music playing]

13
00:00:43,600 --> 00:00:44,960
[music stops]

14
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:48,160
20 YEARS LATER

15
00:00:48,240 --> 00:00:49,680
[sighs sadly]

16
00:01:03,200 --> 00:01:05,520
[soft, haunting music]

17
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:17,440
HONEY, CALL ME. I WANT TO TALK.

18
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:22,080
[keys jingling]

19
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:23,760
[car lock beeps]

20
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:34,800
{\an8}HONEY, CALL ME. I WANT TO TALK.

21
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:36,840
Lucía, on your phone in class?

22
00:01:36,920 --> 00:01:38,080
[all chuckling]

23
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:40,040
[school bell rings]

24
00:01:42,120 --> 00:01:43,360
[phone beeps]

25
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:45,120
Ruth, honey, call me back.

26
00:01:45,760 --> 00:01:46,800
Please.

27
00:01:46,880 --> 00:01:47,880
[phone beeps]

28
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:57,840
[man on radio] <i>And now</i>
<i>the latest on Alejandro Huelva,</i>

29
00:01:57,920 --> 00:02:01,120
<i>the missing nine-year-old boy</i>
<i>who disappeared while on a bike ride</i>

30
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:03,000
<i>on October twenty-third.</i>

31
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:05,520
<i>The search continues,</i>
<i>but remains unsuccessful.</i>

32
00:02:05,600 --> 00:02:08,440
<i>State authorities have been joined</i>
<i>by groups of volunteers,</i>

33
00:02:08,520 --> 00:02:10,600
<i>both local and from neighboring counties,</i>

34
00:02:10,680 --> 00:02:12,760
<i>who have organized</i>
<i>to assist the Civil Guard</i>

35
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:14,720
<i>-in the ongoing search effort.</i>
-[phone rings]

36
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:16,760
[woman, faintly] Alejandro!

37
00:02:17,600 --> 00:02:20,480
- [man] Alejandro!
- [woman] Alejandro!

38
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:22,760
[on radio] <i>If you have information</i>
<i>on the missing boy,</i>

39
00:02:22,840 --> 00:02:27,480
<i>please call the hotline at 984-555-676.</i>

40
00:02:27,560 --> 00:02:30,640
<i>In other news, the fourth quarter</i>
<i>labor report has been released,</i>

41
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:33,880
<i>the unemployment rate unfortunately is…</i>

42
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:36,960
[haunting music playing]

43
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:40,760
[indistinct chatter]

44
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:48,320
{\an8}[music intensifies]

45
00:03:13,080 --> 00:03:18,000
THE TRUTHERS

46
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:20,640
["Amante Bandido" by Miguel Bosé
playing on radio]

47
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:25,960
[music stops]

48
00:03:28,680 --> 00:03:30,520
[dog barking]

49
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:40,560
[phone beeps]

50
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:42,800
[line ringing]

51
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:48,240
-[dance pop music playing loudly]
-[phone ringing]

52
00:03:51,040 --> 00:03:52,080
[phone clicks]

53
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:02,720
Hey, are you okay?

54
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:04,200
Yeah, I'm fine.

55
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:07,600
-I know what you need.
-No.

56
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:09,480
We're not going out tonight.

57
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:11,960
Okay, whatever.

58
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:14,280
-Cheers!
-Cheers!

59
00:04:14,360 --> 00:04:15,600
[techno music playing]

60
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:18,240
-[cellphone chimes]
-Whoo!

61
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:25,960
MOM: RUTH, PLEASE CALL ME.
IT'S IMPORTANT

62
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:27,360
All good?

63
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:31,280
Yeah. Two more!

64
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:33,040
[techno music continues]

65
00:04:41,840 --> 00:04:43,240
[music stops]

66
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:45,080
-You look great.
-Oh, no.

67
00:04:45,160 --> 00:04:47,240
-Yes, you do. [chuckles]
-Fuck!

68
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,160
What time is it?

69
00:04:49,240 --> 00:04:51,960
Yeah, it's bright outside,
so I don't know.

70
00:04:52,040 --> 00:04:55,680
-It's… seven? Eight?
-This wasn't supposed to happen, Rose.

71
00:04:55,760 --> 00:04:57,000
I could have a coffee now.

72
00:04:57,080 --> 00:04:58,880
<i>"Un Americano con leche, por favor."</i>

73
00:04:58,960 --> 00:05:00,480
-Is that how you say it?
-Yes.

74
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:02,160
-Okay.
-[cell phone buzzing]

75
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:04,080
Oh fuck.

76
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:06,320
-I'm gonna get something to eat.
-Uh, yeah.

77
00:05:11,560 --> 00:05:15,280
-What's the matter?
-[man] <i>Uh… Ruth, it… it's Mom.</i>

78
00:05:15,360 --> 00:05:16,280
What?

79
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:17,480
<i>Your mom fell.</i>

80
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:19,360
You mean… What do you mean?

81
00:05:20,680 --> 00:05:22,040
Is she okay, or…

82
00:05:23,520 --> 00:05:25,000
<i>Mom is dead, Ruth.</i>

83
00:05:25,080 --> 00:05:27,560
[somber music playing]

84
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:04,240
[man on PA] <i>Iberia flight 8363</i>
<i>to Madrid is now boarding.</i>

85
00:06:04,320 --> 00:06:07,760
Passengers, please proceed
to gate number B69.

86
00:06:07,840 --> 00:06:09,240
URGENT MISSING

87
00:06:09,320 --> 00:06:11,960
<i>Please proceed to gate B…</i>

88
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:13,840
[train horn blares]

89
00:06:15,840 --> 00:06:18,360
[woman on radio] <i>He went out</i>
<i>on his bike every day after school,</i>

90
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:21,280
<i>but he was gone for hours</i>
<i>and didn't come home for dinner.</i>

91
00:06:21,360 --> 00:06:24,120
<i>And he still hasn't come home.</i>
<i>We know he's out there.</i>

92
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:26,480
<i>If anybody sees him, please…</i>

93
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:28,480
If he's been gone for this long…

94
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:29,720
[clicks teeth]

95
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:32,160
It's awful. The whole town is in shock.

96
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:36,200
They're out there looking every day,

97
00:06:36,280 --> 00:06:38,280
but I don't think there's much hope.

98
00:06:38,360 --> 00:06:40,600
[somber music continues]

99
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:05,800
[music fades]

100
00:07:07,320 --> 00:07:08,880
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

101
00:07:09,840 --> 00:07:10,920
[car door slams]

102
00:07:19,160 --> 00:07:20,160
What happened?

103
00:07:21,080 --> 00:07:22,240
[sighs]

104
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:26,520
We need to be strong.

105
00:07:29,320 --> 00:07:30,600
Especially me.

106
00:07:34,080 --> 00:07:35,640
Why's the Civil Guard here?

107
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:39,560
[camera clicking]

108
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:45,080
Okay. Thanks, Carlos.

109
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:52,680
Look, I'm sorry, but… even though
it looks like it was an accident,

110
00:07:52,760 --> 00:07:54,680
we still have to write a report.

111
00:07:55,720 --> 00:07:57,120
So what happened?

112
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,720
Mm. She slipped in the shower.

113
00:08:01,640 --> 00:08:04,480
It looks as though
she had been drinking a bit.

114
00:08:07,800 --> 00:08:09,240
Uh… impossible.

115
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:11,640
What are you saying?

116
00:08:11,720 --> 00:08:12,840
I mean she, she never…

117
00:08:12,920 --> 00:08:14,480
My mother had stopped drinking.

118
00:08:14,560 --> 00:08:16,360
She'd been drinking again.

119
00:08:16,440 --> 00:08:19,160
[moody music playing]

120
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:20,400
She drank.

121
00:08:20,960 --> 00:08:24,320
[officer] Ruth, it seems that your mother,
around midnight, went upstairs

122
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:26,840
and into the bathroom to take a shower.

123
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:28,960
Shall we go up?

124
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:29,960
Of course.

125
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,760
[officer] Your father
was upstairs, in the attic,

126
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:39,880
and noticed that your mother
was in the shower a long time.

127
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:44,160
[father] I asked if she was all right. She
didn't answer. I could hear water running.

128
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:46,080
I had to break down the door.

129
00:08:49,960 --> 00:08:51,000
She was here.

130
00:08:52,160 --> 00:08:54,760
Not moving. She… she wasn't breathing.

131
00:08:54,840 --> 00:08:57,000
[officer] We presume
that when she slipped,

132
00:08:57,080 --> 00:09:00,120
she fell into the shower screen
and it broke.

133
00:09:00,200 --> 00:09:03,360
The impact when
her head hit the floor, it, well…

134
00:09:03,880 --> 00:09:05,520
She died quickly.

135
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:12,000
Please, you can't really touch anything.
For the moment, sorry.

136
00:09:12,600 --> 00:09:16,360
Sorry, it's just that my mother
never used the bolt on the doors.

137
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:17,920
She, she didn't like it.

138
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,080
She never locked a single
door in this house.

139
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:22,920
-Anyone locked a door, she'd yell at us.
-Honey.

140
00:09:24,400 --> 00:09:27,360
I mean, It's like we're talking
about a whole different person.

141
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:29,760
Ruth.

142
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:31,640
I don't recognize her.

143
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:35,160
It's over two years
since you last came to visit us.

144
00:09:36,120 --> 00:09:37,960
I'd be surprised if you recognized her.

145
00:09:41,760 --> 00:09:44,720
[officer] Now we just have to wait,
there's a ton of paperwork,

146
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:46,800
-mostly tedious stuff.
-[moody music fades]

147
00:09:46,880 --> 00:09:48,800
-[father] Patience.
-Patience. That's it.

148
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:50,080
Of course.

149
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:51,960
I was giving your father the update.

150
00:09:52,040 --> 00:09:56,280
That we still have, uh, paperwork,
routine checks to do, you know.

151
00:09:57,240 --> 00:09:59,680
But once we have
the toxicology report back,

152
00:09:59,760 --> 00:10:01,560
if everything looks all right,

153
00:10:01,640 --> 00:10:04,480
we'll release the body and you
can have her back for the funeral,

154
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:06,080
the wake, everything else.

155
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:07,760
Hopefully, it won't be too long.

156
00:10:07,840 --> 00:10:10,640
In the meantime,
if you need anything at all.

157
00:10:13,760 --> 00:10:14,760
Come on.

158
00:10:15,280 --> 00:10:18,640
-Martín, you know how to find me.
-Thanks again.

159
00:10:18,720 --> 00:10:21,040
-No problem. Bye for now.
-Take care.

160
00:10:22,480 --> 00:10:24,480
[intriguing music playing]

161
00:10:43,320 --> 00:10:44,520
[music fades]

162
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:47,560
Well, if you need anything,
you know where I am.

163
00:10:50,520 --> 00:10:51,520
Dad.

164
00:10:55,880 --> 00:10:57,520
Did something happen yesterday?

165
00:11:00,440 --> 00:11:01,720
What are you asking?

166
00:11:02,800 --> 00:11:04,160
Well, Mom called me.

167
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:06,800
Many times.

168
00:11:06,880 --> 00:11:09,680
And I was having a bad day
and I didn't answer.

169
00:11:10,280 --> 00:11:13,000
And messages, too, on my voicemail.

170
00:11:13,080 --> 00:11:14,600
Well, what did she say?

171
00:11:17,760 --> 00:11:18,880
That we had to talk.

172
00:11:21,160 --> 00:11:22,640
We had a bit of an argument.

173
00:11:23,960 --> 00:11:25,000
About what?

174
00:11:27,440 --> 00:11:29,720
It was about how much she was drinking.

175
00:11:31,040 --> 00:11:33,640
I think that's why
she locked the bathroom door.

176
00:11:33,720 --> 00:11:37,000
Maybe she wanted to keep drinking
without me saying anything.

177
00:11:37,920 --> 00:11:39,520
But her glass was downstairs.

178
00:11:39,600 --> 00:11:40,480
Huh?

179
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:42,440
Her glass, she…

180
00:11:42,520 --> 00:11:44,720
She didn't take it with her,
it was downstairs.

181
00:11:45,760 --> 00:11:47,800
She was drunk. Maybe she forgot it.

182
00:11:48,960 --> 00:11:49,960
Does it matter?

183
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:53,600
It does. It's important.

184
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:57,200
It matters because she called me
and I didn't answer, and…

185
00:11:57,280 --> 00:11:59,960
And I was going
to call her today, and now…

186
00:12:00,040 --> 00:12:02,040
[emotional music playing]

187
00:12:02,640 --> 00:12:03,840
[sobbing]

188
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:15,200
[distant barking]

189
00:12:41,280 --> 00:12:42,360
[music fades]

190
00:12:42,440 --> 00:12:43,560
[sighing]

191
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:55,120
[mother] <i>Ruth, are you</i>
<i>really not going to pick up?</i>

192
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:58,880
<i>God knows what you're doing there,</i>
<i>running around in Berlin, really.</i>

193
00:12:58,960 --> 00:13:01,200
<i>But it's your life,</i>
<i>you do what you need to.</i>

194
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:03,840
<i>You're always blaming me,</i>
<i>saying I'm trying to control you.</i>

195
00:13:03,920 --> 00:13:05,640
<i>But, no.</i>

196
00:13:06,720 --> 00:13:08,240
<i>This is important.</i>

197
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:10,680
<i>Please call me back.</i>

198
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:12,480
<i>It's about your father, Ruth.</i>

199
00:13:12,560 --> 00:13:14,720
<i>-Your father isn't…</i>
-[intriguing music playing]

200
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:17,680
<i>He's not the person he used to be.</i>
<i>He's different.</i>

201
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:19,120
<i>For a while now </i>[sighs]<i>…</i>

202
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:23,000
<i>I didn't wanna say anything, I didn't</i>
<i>wanna worry you. But the truth is…</i>

203
00:13:24,040 --> 00:13:25,080
[mute chime]

204
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:26,120
[unmutes]

205
00:13:26,200 --> 00:13:29,520
<i>I'm sorry. I thought I heard him coming.</i>

206
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:30,760
<i>Ruth.</i>

207
00:13:30,840 --> 00:13:33,560
<i>Listen. Your father…</i>

208
00:13:33,640 --> 00:13:36,920
<i>Your… your father, he's scaring me.</i>

209
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:41,400
<i>Ever since he retired, he spends all day</i>
<i>locked away in the attic.</i>

210
00:13:41,480 --> 00:13:42,960
<i>He's changed so much.</i>

211
00:13:43,040 --> 00:13:45,720
<i>And, I don't know</i>
<i>how to explain it to you, but…</i>

212
00:13:46,600 --> 00:13:49,640
<i>But I'm afraid one of these days</i>
<i>he's gonna do something crazy.</i>

213
00:13:49,720 --> 00:13:51,200
<i>Call me, please.</i>

214
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:52,960
<i>I love you.</i>

215
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:55,040
[intriguing music continues]

216
00:14:07,880 --> 00:14:10,920
[music becomes tense]

217
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:15,440
[door creaking, shuts]

218
00:14:16,520 --> 00:14:18,440
[lock clicking]

219
00:14:32,160 --> 00:14:35,640
CIVIL GUARD - DO NOT ENTER

220
00:14:43,720 --> 00:14:45,920
[tense music continues]

221
00:14:53,920 --> 00:14:55,480
-[knocking]
-[music stops]

222
00:14:55,560 --> 00:14:56,600
Dad?

223
00:15:06,240 --> 00:15:07,560
[door knob rattles]

224
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:21,600
Mm. Did you sleep well?

225
00:15:22,400 --> 00:15:25,480
-[plate clatters]
-Not overdone, just the way you like 'em.

226
00:15:28,360 --> 00:15:29,960
-There you go.
-Thank you.

227
00:15:32,160 --> 00:15:33,400
You want anything else?

228
00:15:33,480 --> 00:15:36,120
-Some orange juice?
-No, I'm not that hungry.

229
00:15:37,760 --> 00:15:39,520
Can I help with anything today?

230
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:41,600
Hm, no, don't worry about it.

231
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:44,640
We're still waiting on the okay
from the sergeant, for now.

232
00:15:45,240 --> 00:15:46,840
If you want, I can do the shopping or…

233
00:15:47,640 --> 00:15:49,440
Or maybe I can help with the greenhouse.

234
00:15:49,520 --> 00:15:53,040
Nah, I stopped taking care of
that thing a few months ago.

235
00:15:55,400 --> 00:15:56,400
Why's that?

236
00:15:57,040 --> 00:15:58,520
I've just been too busy.

237
00:16:00,400 --> 00:16:02,000
You're retired, Dad.

238
00:16:03,160 --> 00:16:05,320
And I'm just supposed
to sit around gardening all day

239
00:16:05,400 --> 00:16:06,640
now that I'm retired?

240
00:16:07,280 --> 00:16:08,280
Eat, please.

241
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:15,320
Last night I heard your mother's voice.

242
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:18,120
In a dream or…?

243
00:16:18,200 --> 00:16:21,680
No. On your phone, it sounded like.

244
00:16:21,760 --> 00:16:23,120
[moody music playing]

245
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:24,520
She left you a message?

246
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:27,400
No.

247
00:16:27,480 --> 00:16:29,600
They were just some old voice notes.

248
00:16:30,120 --> 00:16:31,160
You're sure?

249
00:16:32,440 --> 00:16:33,440
Why?

250
00:16:34,240 --> 00:16:37,120
Because I'm your dad, honey.
I know when you lie to me.

251
00:16:37,800 --> 00:16:41,840
Maybe you could try using that instinct
to know when I'm not feeling like talking.

252
00:16:41,920 --> 00:16:44,080
Why can't you tell me
what she said to you?

253
00:16:44,160 --> 00:16:47,240
-Because it was between me and Mom.
-Yeah, sure, like always.

254
00:16:47,960 --> 00:16:50,720
God forbid I should ever
set foot in your world.

255
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:53,960
You and your mother
constantly at each other's throats.

256
00:16:54,040 --> 00:16:56,960
If I ever tried to intervene,
you'd shut down, you'd both shut down.

257
00:16:57,040 --> 00:16:59,240
Well, it's really not that big a deal.

258
00:16:59,320 --> 00:17:01,200
That's over now, sweetheart.

259
00:17:02,440 --> 00:17:05,880
We can't afford
to have secrets anymore, okay?

260
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,960
Your mother is gone, it's just us now.

261
00:17:10,880 --> 00:17:11,960
Yeah, okay.

262
00:17:12,040 --> 00:17:13,720
[birds chirping]

263
00:17:19,560 --> 00:17:22,400
[mysterious music playing]

264
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:43,640
[father] Ruth.

265
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:48,960
The Civil Guard sergeant called.

266
00:17:50,040 --> 00:17:53,360
The coroner is all finished.
We can go and pick up your mother.

267
00:17:54,360 --> 00:17:56,240
And they didn't find anything odd?

268
00:17:57,760 --> 00:17:59,240
What would they find?

269
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:02,200
I mean, she drank, she fell.

270
00:18:04,440 --> 00:18:07,040
[objects rustling, banging]

271
00:18:07,120 --> 00:18:08,520
[music stops]

272
00:18:13,200 --> 00:18:14,280
Can I help?

273
00:18:14,360 --> 00:18:16,320
Uh, no, it's okay, honey.

274
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:20,200
Hey! Come on. I can do that.

275
00:18:20,280 --> 00:18:22,320
I told you, it's okay.

276
00:18:22,400 --> 00:18:23,360
Here. Give me that.

277
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:27,080
Let's have a race, we'll see who wins.

278
00:18:27,160 --> 00:18:28,720
We could swim for it.

279
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:30,880
Hey, that's no fair.

280
00:18:31,640 --> 00:18:33,640
I'm no mermaid out in the water.

281
00:18:33,720 --> 00:18:35,040
Unlike you, honey.

282
00:18:35,680 --> 00:18:36,840
[Ruth] Mm.

283
00:18:39,920 --> 00:18:42,560
You'd have a chance,
this mermaid's a little out of practice.

284
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:45,200
[object thuds]

285
00:18:46,520 --> 00:18:47,600
What are you doing?

286
00:18:48,280 --> 00:18:50,360
Uh, making my way through this garbage.

287
00:18:52,280 --> 00:18:53,800
Those are Mom's face creams.

288
00:18:53,880 --> 00:18:55,000
Garbage.

289
00:18:55,080 --> 00:18:56,600
-[object thuds]
-Poison.

290
00:18:56,680 --> 00:18:59,400
And those motherfuckers
charge a fortune for 'em.

291
00:18:59,480 --> 00:19:00,680
[object thuds]

292
00:19:00,760 --> 00:19:02,760
Since when do you swear this much?

293
00:19:03,280 --> 00:19:07,120
You realize those bastards
are ruining people's lives?

294
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:09,400
They're bleeding out every last dollar.

295
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:12,520
Who's bleeding people, Dad?

296
00:19:14,600 --> 00:19:16,400
The giant pharma companies.

297
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:19,800
You know what
they've done in America, right?

298
00:19:20,360 --> 00:19:23,400
They have half the country
hooked on opioids,

299
00:19:23,480 --> 00:19:25,080
not to mention the fentanyl.

300
00:19:25,160 --> 00:19:28,760
They drug you, bankrupt you,
and turn you into a zombie.

301
00:19:30,080 --> 00:19:30,920
[thuds]

302
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:33,560
What's that have to do with
the products Mom bought?

303
00:19:33,640 --> 00:19:35,120
Do you know how they make these?

304
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:37,240
Experimenting on animals.

305
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:38,920
Yeah.

306
00:19:39,560 --> 00:19:40,720
And people too.

307
00:19:42,520 --> 00:19:43,440
People?

308
00:19:43,520 --> 00:19:44,840
On children.

309
00:19:46,040 --> 00:19:48,640
Children like Alejandro.
Haven't you heard?

310
00:19:48,720 --> 00:19:50,040
[dramatic music playing]

311
00:19:50,120 --> 00:19:52,120
It's impossible for anyone to miss.

312
00:19:53,320 --> 00:19:55,280
He vanished into thin air.

313
00:19:55,920 --> 00:19:58,400
And guess who just came
to town and set up shop?

314
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:02,600
The headquarters of a multinational
pharmaceutical company.

315
00:20:02,680 --> 00:20:03,640
Coincidence?

316
00:20:04,640 --> 00:20:06,800
No such thing as a coincidence, honey.

317
00:20:07,960 --> 00:20:09,880
There are some links I can send you.

318
00:20:09,960 --> 00:20:12,840
There are millions of videos, of articles.

319
00:20:12,920 --> 00:20:15,720
-People fighting to bring this to light.
-Ah, c'mon, Dad.

320
00:20:16,400 --> 00:20:17,400
Yeah.

321
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:19,840
I don't know why I'm surprised.

322
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:22,560
Exactly like your mother.

323
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:26,480
[object clatters]

324
00:20:29,160 --> 00:20:30,480
[music fades]

325
00:20:30,560 --> 00:20:34,000
Hello, Sergeant, how are you?
It's Ruth, Martín's daughter.

326
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:38,440
My… my dad already told me
that you got the coroner's report back

327
00:20:38,520 --> 00:20:40,080
and it says it was an accident.

328
00:20:40,160 --> 00:20:41,400
[sergeant] <i>That's right.</i>

329
00:20:41,480 --> 00:20:43,600
Yes. Well, I…

330
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:46,760
Tell me if I'm out of line or…
or if it's okay to ask,

331
00:20:46,840 --> 00:20:48,920
but I'd like to know if…

332
00:20:49,960 --> 00:20:54,320
If it's possible for me
to see the report.

333
00:20:54,400 --> 00:20:55,440
Or…

334
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:59,000
Or the photos or… or something, because…

335
00:20:59,480 --> 00:21:02,080
Well, it's just that I'd like…
I'd like to…

336
00:21:02,160 --> 00:21:03,640
know exactly what…

337
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:05,640
what they think happened.

338
00:21:05,720 --> 00:21:06,720
And…

339
00:21:08,200 --> 00:21:09,160
Hello?

340
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:12,480
<i>You wanna see a copy of the report?</i>

341
00:21:13,560 --> 00:21:17,320
Yes, if it's possible,
yes, I'd like to see it.

342
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:19,720
<i>No problem.</i>

343
00:21:20,360 --> 00:21:21,360
Great.

344
00:21:21,440 --> 00:21:23,600
[mysterious music playing]

345
00:21:24,600 --> 00:21:25,800
[call disconnects]

346
00:21:40,840 --> 00:21:44,080
[podcast host] <i>This is a phenomenon</i>
<i>that's been going on for decades,</i>

347
00:21:44,160 --> 00:21:47,040
<i>and only recently has enough</i>
<i>evidence come to light.</i>

348
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:50,160
<i>And all of it has been happening</i>
<i>right under our noses,</i>

349
00:21:50,240 --> 00:21:53,000
<i>across the world in every</i>
<i>first world country.</i>

350
00:21:53,080 --> 00:21:56,120
<i>It's vital we spread the word</i>
<i>to protect our children at all costs.</i>

351
00:21:56,200 --> 00:21:57,200
WAKE UP

352
00:21:57,880 --> 00:22:00,480
[host 1] <i>In Spain alone,</i>
<i>between one and two hundred children</i>

353
00:22:00,560 --> 00:22:02,200
<i>go missing each year.</i>

354
00:22:02,280 --> 00:22:07,200
<i>I'm sure our listeners are wondering</i>
<i>who would kidnap these kids and why.</i>

355
00:22:07,280 --> 00:22:09,240
[host 2] <i>The reason is adrenochrome,</i>

356
00:22:09,320 --> 00:22:12,240
<i>a chemical compound that children</i>
<i>produce when under duress,</i>

357
00:22:12,320 --> 00:22:14,480
<i>but which has</i>
<i>restorative effects on adults.</i>

358
00:22:14,560 --> 00:22:15,840
{\an8}THE NEW CONSPIRACY THEORISTS

359
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:18,920
[host 1] <i>Are we talking about</i>
<i>kidnapping children to scare them?</i>

360
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,600
[host 1] <i>To terrorize, to torture them,</i>
<i>the worst atrocities imaginable.</i>

361
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:24,240
CONSPIRACY THEORIES HAVE EVOLVED

362
00:22:24,320 --> 00:22:27,800
<i>-And when they stop being useful?</i>
-[host 2] <i>They kill them, of course.</i>

363
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:30,800
<i>The number of victims in just</i>
<i>the past few years is incalculable.</i>

364
00:22:30,880 --> 00:22:33,440
<i>But mainstream media</i>
<i>won't tell you the truth.</i>

365
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:36,480
[host 1] <i>No, the media don't want</i>
<i>the truth coming out.</i>

366
00:22:36,560 --> 00:22:39,440
[melancholy piano music playing]

367
00:22:55,080 --> 00:22:57,080
[people chattering]

368
00:22:57,960 --> 00:22:59,560
-I'm sorry.
-Mm.

369
00:23:06,720 --> 00:23:07,720
Hi, Grandma.

370
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:08,960
Hello.

371
00:23:11,480 --> 00:23:12,960
Hi, honey. How are you?

372
00:23:17,880 --> 00:23:19,240
Such a shame, dear.

373
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:21,640
How's Martín been?

374
00:23:21,720 --> 00:23:22,560
Mm…

375
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:24,840
I dunno. I think we're all in shock.

376
00:23:30,360 --> 00:23:32,240
It's been a lot, I guess.

377
00:23:48,120 --> 00:23:49,320
Oh, thank you.

378
00:23:50,720 --> 00:23:52,320
I haven't eaten in two days.

379
00:23:53,560 --> 00:23:56,520
I keep seeing your mother
lying on the floor and, uh…

380
00:23:57,520 --> 00:24:00,400
I don't understand
how it could've happened. I don't get it.

381
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:03,240
Neither do I.

382
00:24:04,600 --> 00:24:06,240
You heard she'd been drinking?

383
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:08,920
Yes.

384
00:24:09,840 --> 00:24:11,800
Look, your mother wasn't doing well.

385
00:24:11,880 --> 00:24:15,560
She was feeling really down, sad.

386
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:18,080
I had no idea.

387
00:24:19,440 --> 00:24:23,160
I know, and it's so weird
for me to be talking about her like this.

388
00:24:23,240 --> 00:24:24,840
Especially in the past tense.

389
00:24:27,360 --> 00:24:28,920
Did she drink because of my dad?

390
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:30,240
Martín, he's…

391
00:24:30,320 --> 00:24:33,600
I don't wanna get started about your dad,
because he got weird.

392
00:24:33,680 --> 00:24:35,440
I don't know. Retirement?

393
00:24:36,120 --> 00:24:38,600
I don't think that he's adjusting.

394
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:42,040
I mean, and the pandemic,
that was hard on all of us.

395
00:24:42,120 --> 00:24:46,480
Did you know we had to take
your mother to get vaccinated in secret?

396
00:24:47,520 --> 00:24:49,080
She was so worried about him.

397
00:24:49,760 --> 00:24:51,360
That he would find out.

398
00:24:52,040 --> 00:24:55,160
She didn't know how he would
take it and then… Bah!

399
00:24:57,920 --> 00:24:58,960
But do…

400
00:25:01,520 --> 00:25:03,040
I don't know, do you think…

401
00:25:04,280 --> 00:25:07,080
When they fought that he got
violent or anything like that?

402
00:25:07,160 --> 00:25:08,120
That he…

403
00:25:08,640 --> 00:25:11,640
I don't really know,
because your mother, you know she…

404
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:14,680
She wouldn't talk about it.
Not to me, not to anyone.

405
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:36,760
[intriguing music playing]

406
00:25:38,080 --> 00:25:40,680
Okay, here it is. The copy of the report.

407
00:25:41,640 --> 00:25:44,160
There are some pictures in there
from when we found her.

408
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:46,240
I wouldn't look, if I were you.

409
00:25:47,920 --> 00:25:49,920
[intriguing music continues]

410
00:26:08,840 --> 00:26:13,000
PROBABLE CAUSE OF DEATH:
SEVERE HEAD TRAUMA FROM ACCIDENTAL FALL

411
00:26:42,440 --> 00:26:44,360
[music fades]

412
00:26:57,720 --> 00:26:58,760
Ruth…

413
00:26:58,840 --> 00:27:00,640
Oh, it's so terrible.

414
00:27:01,680 --> 00:27:03,720
Our deepest condolences.

415
00:27:04,960 --> 00:27:06,840
She worked us so hard.

416
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:08,720
All day swimming laps.

417
00:27:08,800 --> 00:27:11,600
Well, she was very strict.
But such a great coach.

418
00:27:11,680 --> 00:27:12,640
Yeah.

419
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:15,040
[woman] She missed you so much. Well…

420
00:27:15,720 --> 00:27:18,080
Sorry, but do you know who that is,
the group with my dad?

421
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:21,360
Them? Oh, that's his search party.

422
00:27:23,080 --> 00:27:24,120
His search party?

423
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:28,960
I'm not sure if you've heard,
but there's a missing child, and, well…

424
00:27:29,040 --> 00:27:31,440
The neighbors have organized
these groups to look for him.

425
00:27:31,520 --> 00:27:33,600
That's Mariano, the new commissioner.

426
00:27:33,680 --> 00:27:35,720
Luis, from the garage.

427
00:27:35,800 --> 00:27:38,560
-And that's Alfonso, the police doctor.
-[intriguing music playing]

428
00:27:39,200 --> 00:27:40,400
I'm sorry?

429
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:42,800
You know, I mean the…

430
00:27:43,560 --> 00:27:44,920
Oh, what do you call it?

431
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:45,920
The coroner.

432
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:48,040
Coroner.

433
00:27:48,960 --> 00:27:50,040
The coroner.

434
00:27:54,320 --> 00:27:56,480
-Excuse me for just a moment.
-Go ahead.

435
00:28:04,960 --> 00:28:06,960
[paper rustling]

436
00:28:12,280 --> 00:28:13,280
[Ruth] Alfonso.

437
00:28:13,360 --> 00:28:16,000
{\an8}CORONER ALFONSO GARCÍA MARÍN

438
00:28:24,280 --> 00:28:25,720
[music fades]

439
00:28:25,800 --> 00:28:28,080
[man] Our dear Lucía,
may God watch over you.

440
00:28:29,320 --> 00:28:31,160
You will be missed.

441
00:28:31,240 --> 00:28:33,520
Especially by your husband
and by your daughter.

442
00:28:34,560 --> 00:28:36,040
They are not alone.

443
00:28:36,120 --> 00:28:38,040
God smile upon this family

444
00:28:38,640 --> 00:28:40,160
until they are reunited.

445
00:28:41,120 --> 00:28:45,480
Faith is essential in times like these.

446
00:28:46,280 --> 00:28:50,200
It's so important to believe that
there is someone waiting for us.

447
00:28:50,280 --> 00:28:53,040
Back there, standing in the last row,
who is that woman?

448
00:28:54,680 --> 00:28:57,120
[man] It's easy to think of God
only in the hard times.

449
00:28:57,200 --> 00:28:58,280
No idea.

450
00:28:58,800 --> 00:29:00,440
But we must remember…

451
00:29:00,520 --> 00:29:03,240
I saw her back at the house.
At the wake too.

452
00:29:03,320 --> 00:29:06,040
-How orphaned are those without faith?
-Shh.

453
00:29:06,640 --> 00:29:08,840
Or those who worship false idols?

454
00:29:10,480 --> 00:29:13,080
Or those who are swept up by the absurd?

455
00:29:14,080 --> 00:29:17,120
Pursuing who knows what.

456
00:29:18,200 --> 00:29:21,200
Why do we have to sit here
and listen to this bullshit?

457
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:25,840
[priest] To the false prophets,
to the merchants of the temple,

458
00:29:25,920 --> 00:29:28,520
to the ignorants
who claim enlightenment,

459
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:30,800
to them, the Lord has this to say.

460
00:29:32,120 --> 00:29:35,760
"I am the way, and the truth,

461
00:29:36,280 --> 00:29:37,600
and the life."

462
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:39,800
[people murmuring]

463
00:29:44,400 --> 00:29:45,600
[car horn honks]

464
00:29:51,520 --> 00:29:54,000
[dramatic music playing]

465
00:30:01,320 --> 00:30:03,640
[melancholy music playing]

466
00:30:22,440 --> 00:30:25,360
[church bell ringing]

467
00:30:30,960 --> 00:30:32,360
[music stops]

468
00:30:32,440 --> 00:30:33,720
Arón!

469
00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:35,400
Arón!

470
00:30:35,480 --> 00:30:36,920
[footsteps]

471
00:30:41,280 --> 00:30:42,280
Ruth.

472
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:45,280
It's been a minute.

473
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:46,360
Yeah.

474
00:30:52,440 --> 00:30:54,280
Hey, you dealing anymore?

475
00:30:54,360 --> 00:30:57,200
I'll find you something,
but only because it's you.

476
00:30:57,280 --> 00:30:58,800
Because I don't do this now.

477
00:30:58,880 --> 00:31:02,120
I'm moving up in the world.
I have a cleaning job now.

478
00:31:02,200 --> 00:31:03,560
[chuckles]

479
00:31:08,600 --> 00:31:09,600
For you.

480
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:11,560
Thanks.

481
00:31:12,200 --> 00:31:14,640
I'm sorry I wasn't at the funeral.

482
00:31:15,440 --> 00:31:19,240
I thought your mom never really approved
of me, so it just didn't seem right.

483
00:31:19,760 --> 00:31:21,080
But I regret it now.

484
00:31:21,720 --> 00:31:25,480
You aren't going to funerals for the dead,
we go for the people left behind.

485
00:31:26,280 --> 00:31:29,160
And I was so grateful to everyone
who came to the funeral for my dad.

486
00:31:29,240 --> 00:31:30,720
Don't feel bad.

487
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:33,280
You're right,
my mom wasn't your biggest fan.

488
00:31:33,360 --> 00:31:34,720
[chuckles]

489
00:31:35,320 --> 00:31:37,840
Well, I took the fall
for her daughter getting lost.

490
00:31:37,920 --> 00:31:39,160
What're you saying?

491
00:31:39,240 --> 00:31:40,640
I'm not lost, all right?

492
00:31:41,360 --> 00:31:43,800
I suppose it's true
that my life's not a straight line.

493
00:31:43,880 --> 00:31:45,080
Oh, how poetic.

494
00:31:46,040 --> 00:31:49,600
No, seriously. Seriously, I don't blame
her for having an issue with the boyfriend

495
00:31:49,680 --> 00:31:51,200
who introduced you to smoking.

496
00:31:51,280 --> 00:31:52,800
Hmm. Boyfriend?

497
00:31:52,880 --> 00:31:55,680
-Well, fuck buddy, okay? Fuck buddy.
-[laughs]

498
00:31:55,760 --> 00:31:57,640
She wasn't crazy about that either.

499
00:31:58,360 --> 00:31:59,440
[Ruth] Mm-mm.

500
00:32:01,040 --> 00:32:03,960
Lately, the one
that seems to hate me is your dad.

501
00:32:04,680 --> 00:32:05,720
How so?

502
00:32:05,800 --> 00:32:07,800
[quiet dramatic music playing]

503
00:32:07,880 --> 00:32:11,320
I don't know. He seemed less scary
when he was still in the Civil Guard.

504
00:32:11,400 --> 00:32:13,880
He used to offer me
these odd jobs every once in a while.

505
00:32:13,960 --> 00:32:16,440
Security jobs mostly,
A few hours and good pay.

506
00:32:17,320 --> 00:32:19,080
But since I took a job at Certyx…

507
00:32:20,680 --> 00:32:22,960
-Is that the new pharma company?
-Mm-hm.

508
00:32:23,600 --> 00:32:25,080
But he doesn't just ignore me,

509
00:32:25,160 --> 00:32:27,080
it's like he wants to see me dead.

510
00:32:32,080 --> 00:32:33,080
What?

511
00:32:35,360 --> 00:32:37,320
I don't know, I don't know…

512
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:39,240
Maybe my father has a screw loose.

513
00:32:39,320 --> 00:32:42,080
But I just feel like
I'm the one who's going crazy here.

514
00:32:44,680 --> 00:32:46,360
He's been weird, hasn't he?

515
00:32:47,520 --> 00:32:48,720
Different, I guess.

516
00:32:50,040 --> 00:32:51,040
And?

517
00:32:53,400 --> 00:32:55,080
I've even been wondering if he…

518
00:32:58,840 --> 00:33:00,760
I'm not the same person I was either.

519
00:33:04,280 --> 00:33:05,320
You haven't changed.

520
00:33:09,200 --> 00:33:10,120
Hmm?

521
00:33:10,600 --> 00:33:11,640
Oh, shit.

522
00:33:13,960 --> 00:33:14,960
Was it?

523
00:33:17,520 --> 00:33:19,040
I survived colon cancer.

524
00:33:19,600 --> 00:33:20,720
You believe that?

525
00:33:23,680 --> 00:33:25,280
Jesus, I had no idea.

526
00:33:26,720 --> 00:33:29,760
Yeah, well, we hadn't talked in a bit.

527
00:33:29,840 --> 00:33:32,040
Not about to send an email to tell you.

528
00:33:32,120 --> 00:33:36,240
I suppose this bag has changed
my life in a few different ways, but…

529
00:33:36,320 --> 00:33:37,400
Well…

530
00:33:39,360 --> 00:33:41,920
Some days it's the worst thing
that's happened to me.

531
00:33:42,440 --> 00:33:44,000
And sometimes I'm thankful.

532
00:33:45,280 --> 00:33:47,520
It's proof I fought for my life and I won.

533
00:33:48,520 --> 00:33:50,760
That always makes me wanna celebrate.

534
00:33:53,200 --> 00:33:54,160
Oh, really?

535
00:33:54,240 --> 00:33:57,240
[lo-fi rock music playing]

536
00:33:57,320 --> 00:34:00,080
["His Eyes Keep Moving Towards Her"
by Los Cuantos]

537
00:34:04,440 --> 00:34:08,160
<i>♪ And he keeps his eyes to the ground ♪</i>

538
00:34:08,760 --> 00:34:12,920
<i>♪ Looking at his own feet</i>
<i>While walking around ♪</i>

539
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:16,960
<i>♪ He knows every dog shit in town ♪</i>

540
00:34:17,520 --> 00:34:23,840
♪ <i>And he thinks he must be wrong</i>
<i>'Cause with his eyes closed… </i>♪

541
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:26,320
What?

542
00:34:27,080 --> 00:34:28,160
It's just…

543
00:34:29,040 --> 00:34:30,880
Now, ever since I got the bag…

544
00:34:32,600 --> 00:34:34,160
What? Can't you do it?

545
00:34:34,240 --> 00:34:37,160
I don't know. Really, I have no idea.

546
00:34:38,680 --> 00:34:40,920
I haven't hooked up with anyone since.

547
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:42,080
Why's that?

548
00:34:42,640 --> 00:34:43,760
It doesn't…

549
00:34:43,840 --> 00:34:46,000
make me feel very attractive, you know.

550
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:48,040
I don't know.

551
00:34:48,800 --> 00:34:50,960
Well, I think you're hotter than ever.

552
00:34:51,040 --> 00:34:52,080
Really?

553
00:34:52,600 --> 00:34:53,880
Mmm.

554
00:34:53,960 --> 00:34:55,960
[song continues]

555
00:35:06,680 --> 00:35:08,120
[song fades]

556
00:35:09,680 --> 00:35:11,080
[Arón] Here's where I work.

557
00:35:12,520 --> 00:35:14,000
The new building's huge.

558
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:26,040
That was a pretty great night.

559
00:35:26,800 --> 00:35:27,840
[Ruth] Mm.

560
00:35:29,120 --> 00:35:30,200
Mm-mm.

561
00:35:30,920 --> 00:35:31,880
See you around.

562
00:35:31,960 --> 00:35:33,120
See ya. You too.

563
00:35:35,360 --> 00:35:38,000
[melancholy piano music playing]

564
00:35:54,320 --> 00:35:56,320
[music fades]

565
00:35:56,400 --> 00:35:57,760
[birds chirping]

566
00:35:57,840 --> 00:35:59,840
[happy whistling]

567
00:35:59,920 --> 00:36:02,280
[scrubbing]

568
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:03,880
[sighs]

569
00:36:10,360 --> 00:36:12,440
[whistling and scrubbing continue]

570
00:36:16,960 --> 00:36:18,360
[Ruth] What are you doing?

571
00:36:19,840 --> 00:36:21,000
What's it look like?

572
00:36:23,120 --> 00:36:24,440
Bit soon, don't you think?

573
00:36:25,360 --> 00:36:28,600
The sooner the better,
the sooner we can get on with our lives.

574
00:36:30,520 --> 00:36:33,000
And the sooner you
get back to the attic, right?

575
00:36:34,840 --> 00:36:35,880
[sighs]

576
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:44,120
What is it you're doing up there?

577
00:36:47,080 --> 00:36:48,560
Hmm, well I…

578
00:36:48,640 --> 00:36:51,000
I read, watch videos, stay informed.

579
00:36:52,280 --> 00:36:54,200
That's what everyone should be doing.

580
00:36:55,920 --> 00:36:58,080
You need to keep
the door locked to do that?

581
00:36:58,160 --> 00:37:00,800
I don't like people sticking
their nose in my business.

582
00:37:00,880 --> 00:37:02,600
You were the same way.

583
00:37:02,680 --> 00:37:05,720
You made us put locks
on every door in the fucking house.

584
00:37:05,800 --> 00:37:07,320
The "fucking house"?

585
00:37:07,400 --> 00:37:08,720
Yeah.

586
00:37:08,800 --> 00:37:11,800
When I was a fucking teen, maybe.
Not like you.

587
00:37:12,400 --> 00:37:14,400
You never used to talk like that to me.

588
00:37:16,800 --> 00:37:19,480
Well, maybe that's
what you needed to hear, honey.

589
00:37:19,960 --> 00:37:21,280
A few cold, hard truths.

590
00:37:22,960 --> 00:37:24,200
I don't recognize you.

591
00:37:26,400 --> 00:37:28,760
[sighs] But you haven't changed at all.

592
00:37:29,400 --> 00:37:32,360
Your own mother's funeral
and you had somewhere else to be.

593
00:37:32,440 --> 00:37:35,160
[tense music playing]

594
00:37:35,240 --> 00:37:36,400
Gee, thanks.

595
00:37:56,040 --> 00:38:00,200
ADRENALINE - ADRENOCHROME

596
00:38:00,280 --> 00:38:02,280
[tense music continues]

597
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:18,400
[tense music fades]

598
00:38:18,480 --> 00:38:20,200
Uh, Ruth. I…

599
00:38:20,280 --> 00:38:21,400
This is your mom's phone.

600
00:38:21,480 --> 00:38:23,520
I thought you could use it if you wanted.

601
00:38:24,200 --> 00:38:25,400
It's practically new.

602
00:38:25,480 --> 00:38:27,600
And I know yours is getting old.

603
00:38:29,640 --> 00:38:30,720
Thanks, Dad.

604
00:38:32,160 --> 00:38:34,920
-Whoa, this is one of the fancy ones.
-Yeah.

605
00:38:36,120 --> 00:38:38,960
She actually got
pretty annoyed with me about that.

606
00:38:39,040 --> 00:38:41,600
"It's too much to spend
on a phone," she said.

607
00:38:42,480 --> 00:38:43,920
So much bothered her.

608
00:38:44,760 --> 00:38:46,760
-Since when?
-[moody piano music playing]

609
00:38:46,840 --> 00:38:48,840
When it started, she was angry with you.

610
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:51,840
Because you left,
because you had given up on your studies.

611
00:38:51,920 --> 00:38:54,280
You were God knows where
doing God knows what.

612
00:38:54,360 --> 00:38:57,800
But how could you be angry
with someone who wasn't there?

613
00:38:59,600 --> 00:39:02,080
I was the person who stayed here with her.

614
00:39:02,160 --> 00:39:05,000
The only person she could hold
responsible for it all.

615
00:39:05,520 --> 00:39:08,320
She blamed me and said
I wasn't strict enough with you.

616
00:39:09,400 --> 00:39:12,640
It's always easier to blame someone else.

617
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:17,520
It was a difficult time.

618
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:20,880
But don't worry about me.

619
00:39:20,960 --> 00:39:22,520
I'm doing much better now.

620
00:39:24,040 --> 00:39:25,200
I'm okay.

621
00:39:25,280 --> 00:39:27,440
[distant thunder rumbling]

622
00:39:27,520 --> 00:39:28,520
Just a minute.

623
00:39:29,680 --> 00:39:32,760
Uh, do you have
the password for Mom's phone?

624
00:39:32,840 --> 00:39:36,560
Uh… You won't need it.
I… I wiped it yesterday.

625
00:39:37,240 --> 00:39:38,120
Uh…

626
00:39:39,240 --> 00:39:40,960
And everything that was on it?

627
00:39:41,840 --> 00:39:43,640
Your mother's gone, sweetheart.

628
00:39:43,720 --> 00:39:46,160
Why would anyone else
need what was on it now?

629
00:39:46,800 --> 00:39:48,040
What use is it to you?

630
00:39:48,680 --> 00:39:51,240
-Me? Oh, nothing.
-[ominous music playing]

631
00:39:51,320 --> 00:39:53,400
-Never mind.
-All right.

632
00:39:53,480 --> 00:39:55,480
[intriguing music playing]

633
00:40:30,560 --> 00:40:31,560
[engine starts]

634
00:40:31,640 --> 00:40:33,840
["Amante Bandido"
by Miguel Bosé playing]

635
00:40:49,360 --> 00:40:50,600
[song stops]

636
00:40:54,800 --> 00:40:56,920
[tense music playing]

637
00:41:32,640 --> 00:41:35,920
[Ruth] He wiped her phone.
Anything we can do to see what was on it?

638
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:38,840
One thing we can try.
We can see what she had in the cloud.

639
00:41:38,920 --> 00:41:41,000
But the repair shop
could probably do more.

640
00:41:41,080 --> 00:41:44,080
But we can't go into town,
everyone knows my father.

641
00:41:44,160 --> 00:41:45,520
Why does that matter?

642
00:41:48,320 --> 00:41:50,080
What the fuck's going on, Ruth?

643
00:41:53,560 --> 00:41:54,400
[phone chimes]

644
00:41:54,480 --> 00:41:56,760
[Lucía on recording]
<i>I thought your father was coming.</i>

645
00:41:56,840 --> 00:41:59,440
<i>He spends all day locked up in the attic.</i>

646
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:03,240
<i>I'm afraid that, I don't, I don't know,</i>
<i>he'll do something crazy one day.</i>

647
00:42:03,320 --> 00:42:04,320
[phone chimes]

648
00:42:06,040 --> 00:42:09,200
All right. At your dad's age,
that could be anything, Ruth.

649
00:42:09,280 --> 00:42:10,280
Anything at all.

650
00:42:11,880 --> 00:42:15,720
-A divorce, or buying a convertible…
-Yeah, but she said she was scared, Arón.

651
00:42:16,440 --> 00:42:18,440
My mother was never afraid of anything.

652
00:42:19,320 --> 00:42:23,040
Yeah. You hadn't seen her in a while,
I'm just saying.

653
00:42:23,120 --> 00:42:24,720
For fuck's sake, she's my mom.

654
00:42:25,280 --> 00:42:27,440
She used to use the bathroom
with the door open.

655
00:42:28,120 --> 00:42:31,080
She couldn't stand closed doors
and she didn't like secrets.

656
00:42:31,600 --> 00:42:34,680
And I'm sure she hated that my dad
was locking himself upstairs.

657
00:42:36,840 --> 00:42:38,520
What if she went in there?

658
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:39,680
What if she saw something?

659
00:42:39,760 --> 00:42:41,920
Whatever it is my father doesn't
want anybody to see?

660
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:44,000
Maybe they fought
and that's why she called me?

661
00:42:44,960 --> 00:42:46,560
And that's why they killed her?

662
00:42:47,880 --> 00:42:50,520
Slow down, Ruth, come on.
Let's not get crazy.

663
00:42:51,080 --> 00:42:52,680
Have you talked to the Civil Guard?

664
00:42:52,760 --> 00:42:55,440
I can't do that,
they're all buddy-buddy with my father.

665
00:42:55,520 --> 00:42:56,720
I don't know.

666
00:42:56,800 --> 00:42:58,280
Am I crazy for thinking this?

667
00:42:58,360 --> 00:43:02,000
No, no, you're not. I just don't know.
I don't know, Ruth, I don't know.

668
00:43:04,800 --> 00:43:06,680
Is that why you're still in town?

669
00:43:11,640 --> 00:43:14,640
I need to know for sure
that what I'm thinking here isn't true.

670
00:43:15,760 --> 00:43:16,880
Here we go.

671
00:43:16,960 --> 00:43:18,280
What have we got?

672
00:43:18,360 --> 00:43:20,480
It says there are 200 photos.

673
00:43:21,240 --> 00:43:23,080
That doesn't seem like a lot.

674
00:43:23,160 --> 00:43:24,960
Yeah, this was a brand-new phone.

675
00:43:25,840 --> 00:43:27,720
I think it was a Christmas present.

676
00:43:28,480 --> 00:43:30,160
No, looks like that's it.

677
00:43:30,240 --> 00:43:32,680
Could there be another
folder here somewhere?

678
00:43:33,280 --> 00:43:35,600
Something she was trying
to keep hidden? I dunno.

679
00:43:35,680 --> 00:43:37,760
-Wait. What's that?
-Well, let's see.

680
00:43:38,240 --> 00:43:39,320
No name here.

681
00:43:40,080 --> 00:43:41,320
Close your eyes.

682
00:43:41,400 --> 00:43:42,360
Why?

683
00:43:42,440 --> 00:43:44,360
-Just in case.
-In case, what?

684
00:43:44,440 --> 00:43:46,520
What if there are nudes
or something like that?

685
00:43:46,600 --> 00:43:48,920
-Nudes of your mother, your father.
-Be serious.

686
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:50,360
Or even both of them naked.

687
00:43:50,440 --> 00:43:52,520
-You don't want to see that.
-You're an idiot.

688
00:43:52,600 --> 00:43:55,320
Neither do I, for the record,
I swear, neither do I, but…

689
00:43:55,400 --> 00:43:58,120
But if that's what it's gonna
take to marry you, I'll do it.

690
00:43:58,800 --> 00:44:00,000
[scoffs]

691
00:44:00,080 --> 00:44:02,440
Relax, I'm kidding.
Come on, close your eyes.

692
00:44:04,120 --> 00:44:06,040
All right, hurry up. Go on.

693
00:44:07,520 --> 00:44:08,520
And?

694
00:44:09,440 --> 00:44:11,880
-Who is this?
-[mysterious music playing]

695
00:44:12,480 --> 00:44:13,520
[Ruth] Fuck!

696
00:44:15,080 --> 00:44:16,360
Fuck, I knew it!

697
00:44:16,880 --> 00:44:19,040
-I knew it.
-[Arón] What's going on?

698
00:44:19,120 --> 00:44:21,800
I saw this woman.
She was at the wake and the funeral.

699
00:44:21,880 --> 00:44:25,600
I asked my dad who she was
and he lied to me and said he had no idea.

700
00:44:26,080 --> 00:44:27,200
Who the fuck is she?

701
00:44:27,880 --> 00:44:31,280
I don't know, this doesn't give us a name.
Only your mom and dad know.

702
00:44:31,800 --> 00:44:34,280
I have to find out.
I need to figure out who she is.

703
00:44:34,360 --> 00:44:35,840
How do you plan to do that?

704
00:44:35,920 --> 00:44:39,720
I'll show all the photos to my father,
and I'll make him tell me the truth.

705
00:44:40,280 --> 00:44:41,720
Gonna do that on your own?

706
00:44:43,520 --> 00:44:45,520
[mysterious music continues]

707
00:44:51,080 --> 00:44:53,800
Shit, Arón, did you really
have to smoke in the van?

708
00:44:53,880 --> 00:44:55,280
I was nervous.

709
00:44:55,360 --> 00:44:56,520
But I'm good.

710
00:45:00,360 --> 00:45:01,360
[Ruth] Hi, Dad.

711
00:45:02,080 --> 00:45:03,280
Remember Arón?

712
00:45:08,360 --> 00:45:09,680
I invited him to dinner.

713
00:45:10,680 --> 00:45:11,520
Good evening.

714
00:45:12,160 --> 00:45:13,200
[snickers]

715
00:45:13,280 --> 00:45:14,480
That's perfect.

716
00:45:17,200 --> 00:45:19,840
Sorry. I haven't been
doing much cooking lately.

717
00:45:20,720 --> 00:45:22,640
I just throw things together.

718
00:45:22,760 --> 00:45:25,560
Don't worry, Martín,
this is Michelin-star cuisine for me.

719
00:45:25,640 --> 00:45:27,360
Do you eat a lot of junk food?

720
00:45:27,840 --> 00:45:30,720
I clean up shit for work in the morning
and I eat it at night.

721
00:45:30,800 --> 00:45:31,720
-Hm.
-Mm.

722
00:45:32,480 --> 00:45:34,360
Must be why you got cancer.

723
00:45:34,440 --> 00:45:35,520
Come on, Dad.

724
00:45:36,120 --> 00:45:38,560
No, I wasn't saying
that it's your fault, really.

725
00:45:38,640 --> 00:45:41,680
It's the chemicals they're putting
in everything nowadays.

726
00:45:42,560 --> 00:45:44,240
And it's no accident.

727
00:45:44,880 --> 00:45:47,640
You know, they make you sick
so that they can sell you the cure.

728
00:45:48,200 --> 00:45:50,960
At the same time, they're destroying
the National Health System

729
00:45:51,040 --> 00:45:52,600
so that we all have to pay.

730
00:45:54,880 --> 00:45:55,880
Who are "they"?

731
00:45:56,880 --> 00:46:00,560
-The people you've been working for.
-[chuckles] I clean the floors there.

732
00:46:01,920 --> 00:46:03,840
You're working for murderers, y'know.

733
00:46:03,920 --> 00:46:06,880
And they kidnap children too.
Can't forget that.

734
00:46:08,040 --> 00:46:09,520
Do you think this is funny?

735
00:46:09,600 --> 00:46:11,520
Wait, Martín, let me get this straight.

736
00:46:12,560 --> 00:46:15,440
You think my bosses
are responsible for my cancer?

737
00:46:15,520 --> 00:46:17,720
Maybe not your guys exactly, but…

738
00:46:18,640 --> 00:46:21,000
-Well, the pharma companies, you mean.
-Mm-hmm.

739
00:46:21,080 --> 00:46:22,560
And the governments.

740
00:46:22,640 --> 00:46:23,680
[laughs]

741
00:46:24,240 --> 00:46:25,480
Martín, come on now.

742
00:46:25,560 --> 00:46:27,520
I mean who else is to blame?

743
00:46:27,600 --> 00:46:30,760
Well, you know,
it's always easier to blame someone else.

744
00:46:30,840 --> 00:46:33,120
I wish someone was to blame.

745
00:46:33,200 --> 00:46:36,280
I wish there was a cancer lab somewhere,

746
00:46:36,360 --> 00:46:38,640
and we could all go down there
and destroy it.

747
00:46:38,720 --> 00:46:40,240
Just put an end to that shit.

748
00:46:40,760 --> 00:46:42,600
But that's not how it works, Martín.

749
00:46:42,680 --> 00:46:44,120
-It's not?
-No.

750
00:46:44,200 --> 00:46:45,360
How does it work, then?

751
00:46:45,440 --> 00:46:47,040
You get it, and you're fucked.

752
00:46:47,120 --> 00:46:49,320
And you don't know when it'll come back.

753
00:46:49,960 --> 00:46:51,880
You take that fear and you swallow it.

754
00:46:53,040 --> 00:46:55,000
But don't you smoke it
instead of swallowing it?

755
00:46:55,080 --> 00:46:56,200
[chuckles]

756
00:47:00,600 --> 00:47:03,920
Yeah, you smoke.
You sit around on the sofa doing nothing.

757
00:47:04,600 --> 00:47:06,840
You just allow them
to do whatever they want.

758
00:47:06,920 --> 00:47:08,800
And what do you do, remind me?

759
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:13,200
I do my research,
investigate, ask questions, yeah?

760
00:47:13,800 --> 00:47:14,800
Hmm.

761
00:47:15,560 --> 00:47:17,440
That what you're doing
with that friend of yours,

762
00:47:17,520 --> 00:47:20,520
the woman who was at the wake,
the one you said you didn't know?

763
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:25,320
Dad, Mom had photos of you
and this woman together on her phone.

764
00:47:26,360 --> 00:47:27,720
Walking around town.

765
00:47:28,560 --> 00:47:29,800
What are you doing, honey?

766
00:47:29,880 --> 00:47:31,800
Uh… investigating, like you.

767
00:47:33,040 --> 00:47:34,040
Who is she?

768
00:47:36,040 --> 00:47:37,480
Her name is Berta.

769
00:47:39,200 --> 00:47:40,280
Her name is Berta.

770
00:47:40,760 --> 00:47:41,720
Perfect.

771
00:47:43,680 --> 00:47:44,560
Who is Berta?

772
00:47:45,160 --> 00:47:46,480
Berta is a friend.

773
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:47,840
A friend.

774
00:47:47,920 --> 00:47:50,520
Believe it or not, at my age,
you can make new friends.

775
00:47:50,600 --> 00:47:51,480
[Ruth] Hmm.

776
00:47:51,560 --> 00:47:55,200
But people in town could easily get
the wrong idea about something like this,

777
00:47:55,280 --> 00:47:57,200
so I prefer not to say anything.

778
00:47:57,880 --> 00:47:59,640
-But where?
-What?

779
00:47:59,720 --> 00:48:01,480
-Where?
-Where did you meet her?

780
00:48:03,040 --> 00:48:05,160
-On the internet.
-[Ruth] On Tinder?

781
00:48:06,600 --> 00:48:09,560
No. We met on a forum for research.

782
00:48:09,640 --> 00:48:11,040
Who goes on those websites?

783
00:48:11,120 --> 00:48:13,200
More people than you might think.

784
00:48:13,880 --> 00:48:15,080
-Really?
-Yeah.

785
00:48:15,840 --> 00:48:18,280
Most people on there are discreet because…

786
00:48:19,240 --> 00:48:20,320
Because…

787
00:48:21,360 --> 00:48:24,040
Because it's not easy
to talk about certain things.

788
00:48:25,440 --> 00:48:27,920
Because along the way you can lose people.

789
00:48:29,720 --> 00:48:31,440
Is that what happened to you, Dad?

790
00:48:32,920 --> 00:48:34,120
With Mom?

791
00:48:36,320 --> 00:48:37,240
Maybe, yeah.

792
00:48:40,760 --> 00:48:42,600
Berta has lost a lot of people.

793
00:48:43,320 --> 00:48:46,680
She lost her husband,
she lost custody of their two children.

794
00:48:47,600 --> 00:48:49,560
And right now she's feeling very alone.

795
00:48:49,640 --> 00:48:53,360
As her friend, I've been trying to keep
her company. I spend time with her.

796
00:48:53,440 --> 00:48:55,760
I'm helping out a friend, you know.

797
00:48:55,840 --> 00:48:57,120
What's wrong with that?

798
00:49:11,400 --> 00:49:12,760
Tell me what you think.

799
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:15,360
I understand how you feel.

800
00:49:15,440 --> 00:49:16,440
I do.

801
00:49:16,520 --> 00:49:19,080
But deep down,
underneath everything that's…

802
00:49:19,160 --> 00:49:22,560
that's going on with him,
at the end of the day, he's still himself.

803
00:49:23,320 --> 00:49:26,600
He's a Civil Guard,
but he's not a bad guy.

804
00:49:26,680 --> 00:49:29,800
Even in his little fantasy,
he still sees himself as the hero,

805
00:49:29,880 --> 00:49:31,760
saving children from the evil elite.

806
00:49:37,560 --> 00:49:38,680
[chuckles faintly]

807
00:49:39,560 --> 00:49:40,520
Hey.

808
00:49:41,120 --> 00:49:43,800
-Your room brings back some memories.
-[sighs]

809
00:49:44,440 --> 00:49:46,480
I'm getting turned on
thinking about it now.

810
00:49:46,560 --> 00:49:48,840
Your dad next door,
just like it was back then.

811
00:49:48,920 --> 00:49:50,000
Ugh, Arón.

812
00:49:56,120 --> 00:49:57,080
[Ruth sighs]

813
00:49:57,800 --> 00:49:59,600
Do you know how to pick a lock?

814
00:50:01,920 --> 00:50:05,160
I need to get into the attic and
see what my mother saw in there.

815
00:50:06,440 --> 00:50:08,520
[nervously] Why are you telling me this?

816
00:50:09,640 --> 00:50:13,360
It's just I don't think I know anybody
else here who knows how to pick a lock.

817
00:50:14,400 --> 00:50:15,480
And I do?

818
00:50:16,120 --> 00:50:18,240
Why? Because I sold weed?

819
00:50:18,840 --> 00:50:21,680
No. It's just that I was hoping
you could help me.

820
00:50:21,760 --> 00:50:22,760
[Arón chuckles]

821
00:50:23,640 --> 00:50:25,200
Ruth, I'm not a criminal.

822
00:50:26,680 --> 00:50:27,760
[Ruth chuckles]

823
00:50:29,400 --> 00:50:30,800
I know that, Arón.

824
00:50:30,880 --> 00:50:34,360
I don't know, I mean I thought it was
possible you might know a guy, or…

825
00:50:34,440 --> 00:50:38,040
Who do you think I hang around with?
Who do you think I am?

826
00:50:38,120 --> 00:50:40,520
[gloomy music playing]

827
00:50:41,480 --> 00:50:43,440
It doesn't matter. Forget it.

828
00:50:44,320 --> 00:50:45,320
[door opens]

829
00:51:19,480 --> 00:51:23,440
[man on video] <i>To start, we're going</i>
<i>to take the cylinder out very carefully.</i>

830
00:51:23,520 --> 00:51:26,800
<i>You're gonna want to watch</i>
<i>the terminal blocks here and make sure…</i>

831
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:44,160
[clicks]

832
00:51:44,240 --> 00:51:46,240
[tense music playing]

833
00:51:46,760 --> 00:51:48,440
[shudders]

834
00:51:52,840 --> 00:51:55,840
[cell phone buzzing]

835
00:52:04,280 --> 00:52:06,280
[music swelling]

836
00:52:12,480 --> 00:52:13,520
[clicks tongue]

837
00:52:17,240 --> 00:52:18,400
[door opening]

838
00:52:24,600 --> 00:52:26,600
[tense music continues]

839
00:52:27,800 --> 00:52:29,000
[door shuts]

840
00:52:45,200 --> 00:52:47,200
[music becomes quiet]

841
00:53:03,560 --> 00:53:05,440
-[door opens]
-[music fades]

842
00:53:05,520 --> 00:53:07,040
[door creaks]

843
00:53:08,120 --> 00:53:09,120
[door closes]

844
00:53:10,560 --> 00:53:11,600
[lock clicks]

845
00:53:14,560 --> 00:53:15,880
[line ringing]

846
00:53:16,720 --> 00:53:17,720
[Arón] <i>Yeah?</i>

847
00:53:17,800 --> 00:53:20,640
I uh… Sorry, Arón, I, uh…

848
00:53:20,720 --> 00:53:22,400
<i>Did I leave my pass somewhere?</i>

849
00:53:23,280 --> 00:53:24,120
Your what?

850
00:53:24,200 --> 00:53:27,520
<i>My key card,</i>
<i>with the photo and the barcode.</i>

851
00:53:27,600 --> 00:53:30,280
-Um…
<i>-It's on a blue lanyard. I can't find it.</i>

852
00:53:30,360 --> 00:53:33,360
-Where did you leave it?
<i>-Hanging in the van. I can't find it.</i>

853
00:53:33,440 --> 00:53:35,880
<i>I thought I might have left it</i>
<i>at your place yesterday.</i>

854
00:53:35,960 --> 00:53:38,920
Can anyone get into the pharmaceutical
company if they have that pass?

855
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:40,240
<i>Yes, of course.</i>

856
00:53:40,320 --> 00:53:41,640
[mysterious music playing]

857
00:53:41,720 --> 00:53:43,680
-Okay…
<i>-Ruth, what are you thinking?</i>

858
00:53:44,320 --> 00:53:46,320
-It's weird, isn't it?
<i>-What do you mean?</i>

859
00:53:46,400 --> 00:53:48,600
Don't you think it's strange,
that you come here

860
00:53:48,680 --> 00:53:50,640
and suddenly
your pass goes missing?

861
00:53:50,720 --> 00:53:53,000
-Leave the van unlocked?
<i>-I'm sure I left it somewhere.</i>

862
00:53:53,080 --> 00:53:56,280
<i>Just wanted to check if it was there.</i>
<i>I'll get a new one. Bye.</i>

863
00:53:56,360 --> 00:53:59,320
-[disconnect tone]
-[moody dramatic music playing]

864
00:53:59,400 --> 00:54:01,560
-[phone clicks]
-[sighs]

865
00:54:08,880 --> 00:54:11,520
WHAT THEY DON'T WANT US TO KNOW

866
00:54:13,800 --> 00:54:16,840
LAS VEGAS PUBLIC SCHOOL

867
00:54:23,760 --> 00:54:25,320
My ex-wife isn't well.

868
00:54:27,680 --> 00:54:29,960
I asked a judge for a restraining order.

869
00:54:30,040 --> 00:54:31,200
And they granted it.

870
00:54:32,040 --> 00:54:33,560
Right away.

871
00:54:33,640 --> 00:54:37,160
They could clearly see
that she's dangerous.

872
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:39,200
But dangerous how?

873
00:54:39,680 --> 00:54:41,200
She lost her mind.

874
00:54:41,280 --> 00:54:42,440
She was…

875
00:54:42,520 --> 00:54:43,560
[exhales]

876
00:54:43,640 --> 00:54:46,600
She was a wonderful woman,
she was just amazing.

877
00:54:47,800 --> 00:54:49,840
And then she snapped.

878
00:54:50,760 --> 00:54:52,800
She was sick. She was depressed.

879
00:54:52,880 --> 00:54:55,280
It lasted many months.

880
00:54:55,960 --> 00:54:58,160
It was awful, just terrible.

881
00:54:59,280 --> 00:55:02,280
And she finally just shut herself away.

882
00:55:02,360 --> 00:55:04,520
She became obsessed
with these absurd ideas.

883
00:55:04,600 --> 00:55:08,280
She said that birds weren't real,
that they were watching us.

884
00:55:08,960 --> 00:55:12,360
There were these planes that were
fumigating nanotechnology particles

885
00:55:12,440 --> 00:55:13,800
to control us.

886
00:55:13,880 --> 00:55:17,440
Suddenly, there were evil people
who controlled everything, and she…

887
00:55:17,520 --> 00:55:19,280
It was all up to her to defeat them,

888
00:55:19,360 --> 00:55:21,960
and somehow everything
in the world would be right.

889
00:55:23,080 --> 00:55:25,920
Next, she became obsessed
with the disappearances.

890
00:55:26,760 --> 00:55:28,480
With the missing children.

891
00:55:28,560 --> 00:55:31,520
You weren't able to convince her
that it was nonsense, these beliefs?

892
00:55:31,600 --> 00:55:32,680
I wish.

893
00:55:32,760 --> 00:55:36,040
But then she started
overprotecting my children, <i>our </i>children.

894
00:55:36,640 --> 00:55:38,880
They'd come home
and she would search their clothes,

895
00:55:38,960 --> 00:55:40,920
looking in their backpacks for cameras.

896
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:42,200
They couldn't breathe.

897
00:55:42,280 --> 00:55:44,760
She was so… controlling.

898
00:55:46,840 --> 00:55:49,760
Then she renewed her gun license
and had them in the house.

899
00:55:50,440 --> 00:55:53,760
It didn't stop,
things just kept getting worse and worse.

900
00:55:54,360 --> 00:55:57,920
My ex-wife was an explosives expert
when she was in the army.

901
00:55:59,520 --> 00:56:01,880
It seemed like she was gonna
blow something up.

902
00:56:01,960 --> 00:56:03,360
Something, somewhere…

903
00:56:03,840 --> 00:56:05,160
I'm sure that…

904
00:56:06,640 --> 00:56:08,640
I'll see her name in the papers someday.

905
00:56:09,200 --> 00:56:10,280
I know it.

906
00:56:11,880 --> 00:56:14,160
My father is like
a totally different person.

907
00:56:14,960 --> 00:56:16,760
I know it's hard to hear but…

908
00:56:17,840 --> 00:56:19,040
but get away from him.

909
00:56:19,680 --> 00:56:22,280
Run away. As far as you can.

910
00:56:32,520 --> 00:56:33,520
[gunshot]

911
00:56:34,400 --> 00:56:36,400
[distant dogs barking]

912
00:56:48,920 --> 00:56:49,920
[gun shot]

913
00:57:00,160 --> 00:57:01,800
-[gun shot]
-[pottery breaking]

914
00:57:03,840 --> 00:57:05,000
What are you doing?

915
00:57:06,720 --> 00:57:07,760
Practicing.

916
00:57:08,560 --> 00:57:09,560
Something wrong?

917
00:57:12,520 --> 00:57:14,320
I've never seen you shoot before.

918
00:57:14,920 --> 00:57:16,000
[scoffs]

919
00:57:22,720 --> 00:57:25,560
They didn't make you give back
your gun when you retired?

920
00:57:26,960 --> 00:57:29,400
You never know when
it might be good to have around.

921
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:38,680
[suspenseful music playing]

922
00:57:44,840 --> 00:57:46,520
-[gun shot]
-[pottery breaking]

923
00:58:09,640 --> 00:58:11,400
[faint creaking]

924
00:58:13,160 --> 00:58:14,160
[music fades]

925
00:58:14,240 --> 00:58:16,240
[footsteps approaching]

926
00:58:18,400 --> 00:58:20,680
[floor boards creaking]

927
00:58:28,840 --> 00:58:30,840
[floorboards creaking]

928
00:58:42,040 --> 00:58:43,800
[paper rustling]

929
00:59:04,480 --> 00:59:07,000
[tense music playing]

930
00:59:33,960 --> 00:59:35,280
Good night, Ruth.

931
00:59:44,120 --> 00:59:45,400
[footsteps receding]

932
00:59:45,480 --> 00:59:47,200
[music stops]

933
00:59:48,920 --> 00:59:50,000
[exhales]

934
00:59:50,640 --> 00:59:52,680
[Ruth] I need a few more days, I can't…

935
00:59:53,560 --> 00:59:56,800
My mom just died.
I'm… I'm helping my dad here, and…

936
00:59:57,840 --> 01:00:00,160
Okay, fine, fire me. Like… [scoffs]

937
01:00:00,240 --> 01:00:02,320
You're not the only shitty club in Berlin.

938
01:00:02,400 --> 01:00:03,400
Yes.

939
01:00:05,280 --> 01:00:06,120
[phone clicks]

940
01:00:10,240 --> 01:00:12,640
Who was that on the phone?
Is something wrong?

941
01:00:12,720 --> 01:00:15,120
No. It was just my job in Berlin.

942
01:00:15,680 --> 01:00:16,680
Uh-huh.

943
01:00:20,240 --> 01:00:21,520
Where are you going?

944
01:00:22,040 --> 01:00:24,480
We're still out looking for Alejandro.

945
01:00:25,040 --> 01:00:27,400
Uh… I'm headed to the lake.

946
01:00:27,480 --> 01:00:30,480
You wanna come?
You loved it when you were little.

947
01:00:32,080 --> 01:00:33,080
Um…

948
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:38,120
Well, mm, okay.

949
01:00:38,200 --> 01:00:40,200
[intriguing music playing]

950
01:00:44,480 --> 01:00:48,440
[Martín] We've combed over each inch
of the forest and we've found nothing.

951
01:00:48,520 --> 01:00:52,640
If he had gotten lost,
or fallen, or he had died somehow,

952
01:00:52,720 --> 01:00:55,120
well, then we would have
found his body already.

953
01:00:55,200 --> 01:00:56,680
[music stops]

954
01:00:56,760 --> 01:00:58,560
So, what are we doing here?

955
01:00:58,640 --> 01:01:00,960
-There are these old tunnels…
-Old tunnels?

956
01:01:01,040 --> 01:01:03,360
Yeah. They're hundreds of years old.

957
01:01:03,440 --> 01:01:07,960
During the war, the Maquis used them
to secretly go see their families in town.

958
01:01:08,040 --> 01:01:09,360
Here.

959
01:01:11,040 --> 01:01:12,040
Look at this.

960
01:01:12,920 --> 01:01:15,320
Do you know what's there now,
on the other end?

961
01:01:15,400 --> 01:01:17,280
-What?
-The pharma company.

962
01:01:17,800 --> 01:01:19,800
[melancholy music playing]

963
01:01:21,320 --> 01:01:22,600
Right.

964
01:01:22,680 --> 01:01:23,840
Let's go.

965
01:01:34,520 --> 01:01:36,760
NO SWIMMING

966
01:01:36,840 --> 01:01:37,880
[Ruth sighs]

967
01:01:51,200 --> 01:01:52,840
Is that enough for today, maybe?

968
01:01:54,520 --> 01:01:57,520
What if the entrance to the tunnels
was somewhere in the lake?

969
01:01:58,640 --> 01:02:00,840
They said there were spills
a few years back.

970
01:02:00,920 --> 01:02:03,040
That's why nobody swims here anymore.

971
01:02:03,840 --> 01:02:07,360
People use it as a dump,
but what if it's just a cover-up

972
01:02:07,440 --> 01:02:10,600
so that no one actually goes in the water
and finds the tunnels?

973
01:02:13,160 --> 01:02:15,440
I'll have to come back with a wetsuit.

974
01:02:15,520 --> 01:02:16,960
You know what?

975
01:02:17,040 --> 01:02:18,560
That won't be necessary.

976
01:02:20,520 --> 01:02:21,680
What're you doing?

977
01:02:22,280 --> 01:02:24,720
-Finding those tunnels.
-What are you talking about?

978
01:02:25,240 --> 01:02:27,760
Come on,
you can't go in there, it's filthy!

979
01:02:29,920 --> 01:02:31,840
Where are the tunnels, Dad?

980
01:02:31,920 --> 01:02:34,080
This way? Or over here?

981
01:02:36,800 --> 01:02:38,560
What do you think you're doing?

982
01:02:38,640 --> 01:02:40,360
The same thing as you!

983
01:02:40,440 --> 01:02:42,760
The same insane shit
you pull every single day!

984
01:02:42,840 --> 01:02:44,720
It's not so funny, is it?

985
01:02:44,800 --> 01:02:47,240
[melancholy music continues]

986
01:02:53,920 --> 01:02:55,400
Well, I don't see anything.

987
01:02:57,440 --> 01:02:59,040
Or maybe over here?

988
01:02:59,120 --> 01:03:00,120
Ah!

989
01:03:01,920 --> 01:03:03,040
[Martín] What's wrong?

990
01:03:05,720 --> 01:03:06,720
[groans]

991
01:03:10,160 --> 01:03:12,320
-I cut myself.
-Well, I told you.

992
01:03:19,400 --> 01:03:21,480
[thunder rumbling]

993
01:03:23,880 --> 01:03:25,160
[Ruth inhales sharply]

994
01:03:29,080 --> 01:03:30,400
Time to go home, yeah?

995
01:03:31,000 --> 01:03:32,040
What?

996
01:03:32,120 --> 01:03:34,360
There's all kinds
of nasty crap in the water.

997
01:03:34,440 --> 01:03:37,320
I know. In fact, I warned you.

998
01:03:37,400 --> 01:03:39,560
We have to clean this
so it doesn't get infected.

999
01:03:39,640 --> 01:03:40,880
Just a scrape.

1000
01:03:40,960 --> 01:03:44,360
I wanna check something out up there.
Hurry up, it's gonna rain.

1001
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:48,040
[sighs]

1002
01:03:57,320 --> 01:04:01,640
Seems like the only thing you care about
is your obsession with finding this kid.

1003
01:04:01,720 --> 01:04:05,040
Mom's barely in the ground and you're back
out here searching already.

1004
01:04:05,120 --> 01:04:08,200
I don't know, it seems like
you're pissed off about Mom

1005
01:04:08,280 --> 01:04:10,800
only because it interrupted
your search for two days.

1006
01:04:10,880 --> 01:04:13,720
Are you telling me that
my wife's death doesn't matter to me?

1007
01:04:13,800 --> 01:04:16,440
How come you care
so much about this kid, Dad?

1008
01:04:17,320 --> 01:04:19,040
Are you trying to impress her?

1009
01:04:19,120 --> 01:04:20,120
Who do you mean?

1010
01:04:21,240 --> 01:04:22,600
Your new friend, Berta.

1011
01:04:22,680 --> 01:04:24,720
Did she brainwash you, huh, Dad?

1012
01:04:25,640 --> 01:04:28,280
I don't know, tell me.
Are you in love or something?

1013
01:04:28,800 --> 01:04:31,120
The only woman I've ever loved
was your mother.

1014
01:04:31,200 --> 01:04:32,720
-Hm.
-In spite of the drinking.

1015
01:04:33,360 --> 01:04:37,320
In spite of her suddenly being so devout
she would never miss a Sunday mass.

1016
01:04:37,400 --> 01:04:39,760
Your mom hadn't been well
for a long time, Ruth.

1017
01:04:40,280 --> 01:04:41,520
Not since you left.

1018
01:04:42,880 --> 01:04:44,600
Oh, so now it's all my fault?

1019
01:04:45,320 --> 01:04:47,040
You wanna know why I left home?

1020
01:04:47,120 --> 01:04:50,600
Because I wanted to quit swimming.
But of course you'd never allow that.

1021
01:04:50,680 --> 01:04:53,360
I wasn't happy, Dad. I wanted my own life.

1022
01:04:54,800 --> 01:04:56,760
Your mother adored you, Ruth.

1023
01:04:57,720 --> 01:05:01,360
You were the light of her life.
When you left, you left her in the dark.

1024
01:05:01,440 --> 01:05:03,800
Does it surprise you
that she'd been drinking?

1025
01:05:06,080 --> 01:05:09,760
Maybe she started drinking because she
couldn't stand being with an angry old man

1026
01:05:09,840 --> 01:05:13,520
who was getting crazier every day
with his conspiracy theory bullshit.

1027
01:05:13,600 --> 01:05:17,000
Do you know how hard it is to love
someone who looks at you like that?

1028
01:05:17,080 --> 01:05:19,800
After their love and respect
for you goes away?

1029
01:05:19,880 --> 01:05:22,400
Who only sees you
as a useless old man all of a sudden?

1030
01:05:26,160 --> 01:05:28,160
[thunder rumbling]

1031
01:05:30,920 --> 01:05:34,440
I guess it's my fault that you've become
so sick in the head now, too, right?

1032
01:05:34,520 --> 01:05:36,160
I'm completely sane.

1033
01:05:36,240 --> 01:05:38,600
More sane than ever.
Because now I'm awake.

1034
01:05:38,680 --> 01:05:42,360
It's you and the rest of them
who still prefer living in ignorance,

1035
01:05:42,440 --> 01:05:45,000
choosing to ignore the pain
of those children, their families.

1036
01:05:45,080 --> 01:05:49,120
You gotta be kidding, stop. I can't listen
to you spouting the same bullshit!

1037
01:05:49,200 --> 01:05:50,200
I'm not crazy!

1038
01:05:50,800 --> 01:05:52,920
If there was an epidemic
of missing children,

1039
01:05:53,000 --> 01:05:55,640
it would be all over the front page
of every newspaper.

1040
01:05:55,720 --> 01:05:57,520
You're so naive, honey.

1041
01:05:57,600 --> 01:06:00,920
Do I really have to explain
to you how the world works?

1042
01:06:01,000 --> 01:06:02,320
[thunder rumbling]

1043
01:06:02,400 --> 01:06:06,480
I'd prefer to think that you are naive,
and not something worse.

1044
01:06:06,560 --> 01:06:08,240
[dramatic music playing]

1045
01:06:08,320 --> 01:06:10,480
Okay, great, so now
you're suspicious of me?

1046
01:06:11,520 --> 01:06:14,480
Of course, Dad, everyone here
except for you has been bribed.

1047
01:06:14,560 --> 01:06:16,160
Everyone's an idiot except you.

1048
01:06:16,240 --> 01:06:18,160
Have you looked in the mirror lately?

1049
01:06:18,640 --> 01:06:20,360
Have you seen what you look like?

1050
01:06:20,440 --> 01:06:23,400
Because you don't exactly look
like a genius to me right now.

1051
01:06:23,480 --> 01:06:27,440
You're not this prophet everyone should
follow because only you know the truth.

1052
01:06:28,200 --> 01:06:31,640
You're just an old man locked in an attic
doing God knows what up there.

1053
01:06:31,720 --> 01:06:33,440
That's the kind of guy you've become.

1054
01:06:34,440 --> 01:06:37,160
You want to know
what I do in the attic, is that it?

1055
01:06:37,920 --> 01:06:40,640
Is that why you tried
to break in yesterday, huh?

1056
01:06:43,040 --> 01:06:44,840
So you've been spying on me, then?

1057
01:06:45,560 --> 01:06:47,160
-Perfect.
-Where are you going?

1058
01:06:47,240 --> 01:06:49,800
-Get your fucking hands off!
-You'll get lost! Ruth!

1059
01:06:52,120 --> 01:06:54,080
-Ruth. Ruth!
-Leave me alone!

1060
01:06:55,760 --> 01:06:56,600
Ruth.

1061
01:06:57,600 --> 01:06:58,560
Ruth!

1062
01:06:59,200 --> 01:07:00,040
Come back!

1063
01:07:00,640 --> 01:07:01,720
Leave me alone!

1064
01:07:08,560 --> 01:07:09,960
-[grunts]
-Ruth!

1065
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:27,080
[dramatic music fades]

1066
01:07:27,160 --> 01:07:30,080
[man] You lost consciousness,
but you're looking okay now.

1067
01:07:30,160 --> 01:07:34,040
You'll need to take it easy for at least
a couple of days, lay off that ankle.

1068
01:07:34,840 --> 01:07:37,680
Take one painkiller
every eight hours if it hurts.

1069
01:07:37,760 --> 01:07:39,760
And your dad should make tea for you.

1070
01:07:39,840 --> 01:07:41,160
He's good with herbs.

1071
01:07:41,240 --> 01:07:42,840
But, above all, rest.

1072
01:07:42,920 --> 01:07:45,360
We want that ankle
to heal properly, all right?

1073
01:07:48,040 --> 01:07:49,040
Yes, okay.

1074
01:07:51,080 --> 01:07:53,080
[somber music playing]

1075
01:07:54,360 --> 01:07:55,920
[Ruth inhales sharply]

1076
01:08:12,280 --> 01:08:13,760
[car chirps]

1077
01:09:03,040 --> 01:09:05,280
[unsettling music playing]

1078
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:28,360
[music fades]

1079
01:09:28,440 --> 01:09:31,000
Why the fuck is the house
filled with cameras, Dad?

1080
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:34,360
Are you spying on me
or were you spying on Mom?

1081
01:09:34,840 --> 01:09:38,200
[sighs] Why would I do that?
Stop acting like a child, will ya?

1082
01:09:38,280 --> 01:09:40,000
I'm the one acting like a child?

1083
01:09:40,080 --> 01:09:42,080
I put them up for security.

1084
01:09:42,160 --> 01:09:45,400
Because I was afraid that
those people would be coming after us.

1085
01:09:45,480 --> 01:09:46,520
For God's sake…

1086
01:09:46,600 --> 01:09:49,040
-See? I knew you wouldn't believe me.
-[scoffs]

1087
01:09:49,120 --> 01:09:50,600
That's why I didn't tell you.

1088
01:09:50,680 --> 01:09:53,760
But who exactly
is gonna come after us, Dad? Who?

1089
01:09:53,840 --> 01:09:56,440
-The pharmaceutical company?
-And the politicians.

1090
01:09:56,520 --> 01:09:59,400
-Oh.
-And the police. They can bribe anyone.

1091
01:09:59,480 --> 01:10:01,160
The ones you least suspect.

1092
01:10:02,120 --> 01:10:03,560
Just think about it.

1093
01:10:04,120 --> 01:10:06,520
They're committing atrocities on kids.

1094
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:10,520
They're capable of doing anything
to people who oppose their mission.

1095
01:10:11,040 --> 01:10:12,480
And they know I'm onto them.

1096
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:15,840
I've had to be extra careful
since they caught me looking around.

1097
01:10:15,920 --> 01:10:20,760
A guard asked me for my ID. I refused,
but they know who I am and where I live.

1098
01:10:24,600 --> 01:10:26,560
Why were you there in the first place?

1099
01:10:27,120 --> 01:10:29,800
The tunnels connect there,
to the basement of the Certyx building.

1100
01:10:29,880 --> 01:10:31,720
Come on, stop it. I've had enough.

1101
01:10:32,360 --> 01:10:34,720
I'm not gonna sit with a poker face
while you go on and on

1102
01:10:34,800 --> 01:10:36,520
about abandoned tunnels, kids taken.

1103
01:10:36,600 --> 01:10:39,280
-I can't do it. I don't understand you.
-You're not listening.

1104
01:10:39,360 --> 01:10:40,560
They're very dangerous.

1105
01:10:41,160 --> 01:10:44,120
The only one following me around
is your friend Berta.

1106
01:10:44,200 --> 01:10:46,120
She's protecting you, Ruth.

1107
01:10:47,680 --> 01:10:48,880
Protecting?

1108
01:10:48,960 --> 01:10:51,520
She's just been trying
to make sure you're all right.

1109
01:10:51,600 --> 01:10:54,680
And because you're my daughter,
that makes you a target, Ruth.

1110
01:11:01,080 --> 01:11:04,280
Were the cameras recording everything
on the night that Mom died?

1111
01:11:05,560 --> 01:11:07,960
-Of course.
-[intriguing music playing]

1112
01:11:08,040 --> 01:11:09,120
What do they show?

1113
01:11:09,200 --> 01:11:12,320
They show your mom
going into the bathroom.

1114
01:11:12,400 --> 01:11:13,440
That's all.

1115
01:11:15,040 --> 01:11:16,560
Do the Civil Guard know about it?

1116
01:11:16,640 --> 01:11:20,360
Yeah. They have all the footage.
That was the first thing I did, obviously.

1117
01:11:21,480 --> 01:11:23,320
Why didn't you tell me anything? Hm?

1118
01:11:23,400 --> 01:11:25,920
Because you wouldn't
have believed anything I said.

1119
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:29,640
[intriguing music fades]

1120
01:11:31,840 --> 01:11:33,360
-[Ruth] Thank you.
-Of course.

1121
01:11:34,640 --> 01:11:35,720
I have it here.

1122
01:11:36,880 --> 01:11:39,560
This video shows your mom
in the bathroom already.

1123
01:11:40,120 --> 01:11:41,280
This was the day…

1124
01:11:42,200 --> 01:11:44,000
-That she died?
-Yes, that's right.

1125
01:11:54,400 --> 01:11:56,280
-Is it muted?
-[officer] There's no audio.

1126
01:11:56,360 --> 01:11:59,200
So we don't know if she said
something through the door.

1127
01:12:00,040 --> 01:12:02,200
What if my father's just
trying to put on a show?

1128
01:12:02,280 --> 01:12:05,640
Well, that would mean that your father's
planned around the cameras,

1129
01:12:05,720 --> 01:12:10,240
in order to give himself an alibi, so he
could then kill your mother in cold blood.

1130
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:12,280
Is that what you think?

1131
01:12:13,200 --> 01:12:17,040
No, but, my mom locks the door,
and that's it?

1132
01:12:17,640 --> 01:12:19,440
-Why does she fall?
-The alcohol.

1133
01:12:20,240 --> 01:12:22,880
Yeah, but my mom
couldn't have been drinking that much.

1134
01:12:23,680 --> 01:12:24,600
Okay.

1135
01:12:26,440 --> 01:12:28,880
This footage was recorded
a few days earlier.

1136
01:12:28,960 --> 01:12:30,600
It might be hard to watch.

1137
01:12:35,160 --> 01:12:38,080
She'd obviously also
been drinking that day.

1138
01:12:38,160 --> 01:12:40,160
[soft emotional piano music playing]

1139
01:12:53,400 --> 01:12:56,160
-Can you please turn it off?
-Of course, yes. I'm sorry.

1140
01:12:56,920 --> 01:12:58,800
Look, maybe… [sighs]

1141
01:12:58,880 --> 01:13:00,520
I'm just being nosy here…

1142
01:13:02,640 --> 01:13:04,360
But is everything okay at home?

1143
01:13:06,520 --> 01:13:09,000
We're here,
if there's anything we can do for you.

1144
01:13:09,080 --> 01:13:10,520
You know where to find us.

1145
01:13:11,280 --> 01:13:12,320
Okay?

1146
01:13:17,280 --> 01:13:20,520
[Martín] What were you thinking?
Driving with your foot like that?

1147
01:13:21,600 --> 01:13:23,000
You heard the doctor.

1148
01:13:25,960 --> 01:13:27,920
Did you want to get in an accident?

1149
01:13:28,520 --> 01:13:29,680
Want me to lose you too?

1150
01:13:29,760 --> 01:13:31,600
I needed to see for myself.

1151
01:13:32,440 --> 01:13:33,440
See what?

1152
01:13:34,480 --> 01:13:37,400
That your mother had been drinking
until she blacked out?

1153
01:13:37,480 --> 01:13:38,760
You needed to see that?

1154
01:13:39,280 --> 01:13:42,360
That's what I've been trying
to protect you from, sweetheart.

1155
01:13:42,440 --> 01:13:43,720
Seeing moments like that…

1156
01:13:43,800 --> 01:13:45,520
You didn't need to know about it.

1157
01:13:46,120 --> 01:13:48,200
I don't want you
to remember her like that.

1158
01:13:48,720 --> 01:13:49,720
I'm sorry, Dad.

1159
01:13:51,040 --> 01:13:52,960
Promise me you'll take it easy.

1160
01:13:53,560 --> 01:13:55,520
And give your head a rest as well.

1161
01:13:56,400 --> 01:13:58,520
Take a bath, relax. Hm?

1162
01:14:00,120 --> 01:14:02,440
Drink your tea, please, it'll help you.

1163
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:07,000
[somber music playing]

1164
01:14:21,040 --> 01:14:22,040
[door closing]

1165
01:14:33,200 --> 01:14:34,440
[gasps]

1166
01:14:34,520 --> 01:14:36,760
[unsettling music playing]

1167
01:14:40,520 --> 01:14:42,960
[breathing shakily]

1168
01:14:58,400 --> 01:14:59,720
[banging on door]

1169
01:15:01,360 --> 01:15:03,040
[panting]

1170
01:15:03,120 --> 01:15:05,560
[Martín, faintly]
Ruth, do you need anything?

1171
01:15:07,560 --> 01:15:09,120
[knocking on door]

1172
01:15:09,200 --> 01:15:10,680
[Martín] Honey, are you okay?

1173
01:15:12,280 --> 01:15:13,760
Ruth, say something.

1174
01:15:13,840 --> 01:15:15,320
[banging on door]

1175
01:15:15,400 --> 01:15:17,000
[phone ringing]

1176
01:15:17,080 --> 01:15:19,440
-[Arón on phone] <i>Ruth?</i>
-[banging continues]

1177
01:15:21,280 --> 01:15:22,880
<i>Are you okay? What's wrong?</i>

1178
01:15:23,720 --> 01:15:26,680
She wouldn't open the door,
now she's locked herself in her room.

1179
01:15:36,160 --> 01:15:37,520
[Ruth] It's so fucking weird.

1180
01:15:37,600 --> 01:15:41,080
I was fine. I was fine,
and I drank my dad's fucking herbal tea,

1181
01:15:41,160 --> 01:15:42,920
and then I started to feel dizzy.

1182
01:15:43,400 --> 01:15:44,400
You know?

1183
01:15:44,480 --> 01:15:46,400
-Okay.
-Everything started spinning.

1184
01:15:46,480 --> 01:15:49,960
I was staggering around,
just like my mom was in the videos.

1185
01:15:50,040 --> 01:15:53,720
So now I'm starting to think that maybe
my dad could have given her something.

1186
01:15:53,800 --> 01:15:57,000
Something that his friend the coroner
left off of the fucking report.

1187
01:15:57,080 --> 01:15:59,160
-And that's why it wasn't there.
-Hang on.

1188
01:15:59,240 --> 01:16:01,320
I don't think I'm following all of this.

1189
01:16:02,000 --> 01:16:03,200
And I'm a little high.

1190
01:16:03,280 --> 01:16:06,480
I thought, in the video,
you can see your dad knocking on the door

1191
01:16:06,560 --> 01:16:09,400
-and your mother doesn't answer. She…
-Who told you that?

1192
01:16:10,880 --> 01:16:13,040
Because the video doesn't have any audio.

1193
01:16:13,680 --> 01:16:16,000
And maybe he was doing
this whole performance.

1194
01:16:16,080 --> 01:16:18,040
Banging on the door,
breaking the door down.

1195
01:16:18,120 --> 01:16:20,320
When he sees her in there
and she can't move,

1196
01:16:20,400 --> 01:16:23,280
he knows he's away from the cameras
and kills her in cold blood.

1197
01:16:23,360 --> 01:16:26,280
But, Ruth,
Ruth, are you listening to yourself?

1198
01:16:26,360 --> 01:16:28,520
-Do you hear what you're saying?
-He drugged me.

1199
01:16:28,600 --> 01:16:30,560
He drugged me. I couldn't stand up.

1200
01:16:30,640 --> 01:16:32,600
Look, I don't know. Were you smoking?

1201
01:16:32,680 --> 01:16:35,920
-Or did you have anything else today?
-I didn't smoke anything.

1202
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:37,120
Nothing.

1203
01:16:37,800 --> 01:16:39,080
A painkiller.

1204
01:16:39,160 --> 01:16:40,320
Just a painkiller.

1205
01:16:41,160 --> 01:16:44,120
One from the doctor
and they gave me another at the station.

1206
01:16:44,200 --> 01:16:45,640
Then maybe that was it.

1207
01:16:47,800 --> 01:16:49,000
You don't believe me?

1208
01:16:49,680 --> 01:16:50,880
Huh?

1209
01:16:50,960 --> 01:16:52,640
I saw you talking to my father.

1210
01:16:53,360 --> 01:16:54,880
I saw you guys chat.

1211
01:16:55,520 --> 01:16:58,040
Your dad's just really worried
about you. I'm sure.

1212
01:16:58,120 --> 01:16:59,240
Are you sure?

1213
01:16:59,720 --> 01:17:00,560
Yes.

1214
01:17:00,640 --> 01:17:01,880
Did he give you a job?

1215
01:17:02,720 --> 01:17:04,000
Look, all right, enough.

1216
01:17:04,520 --> 01:17:06,120
Okay, Ruth. That's enough.

1217
01:17:06,200 --> 01:17:08,360
Next time you think
your dad wants to kill you,

1218
01:17:08,440 --> 01:17:11,320
or he's seeing aliens
or any of that shit, call someone else.

1219
01:17:11,960 --> 01:17:13,960
Because I'm tired of it, Ruth, honestly.

1220
01:17:14,040 --> 01:17:17,840
I have to come running whenever
you want a locksmith, weed, to get laid.

1221
01:17:19,800 --> 01:17:20,800
Yeah.

1222
01:17:22,600 --> 01:17:25,400
So I guess you're the one
who's been taken advantage of.

1223
01:17:26,200 --> 01:17:29,600
Because everything you do is so selfless,
isn't that right, Arón?

1224
01:17:29,680 --> 01:17:31,320
[moody dramatic music playing]

1225
01:17:31,400 --> 01:17:34,960
Not because you think
maybe you and me could get back together.

1226
01:17:36,120 --> 01:17:37,000
[scoffs]

1227
01:17:37,080 --> 01:17:38,360
I'm done, Ruth.

1228
01:17:50,400 --> 01:17:51,840
[door closes]

1229
01:17:55,040 --> 01:17:56,320
[vehicle door opens]

1230
01:17:57,080 --> 01:17:58,440
[vehicle door closes]

1231
01:17:59,040 --> 01:18:00,440
[engine starts]

1232
01:18:06,760 --> 01:18:07,920
[groans faintly]

1233
01:18:11,320 --> 01:18:12,360
[lock clicks]

1234
01:18:25,960 --> 01:18:27,080
[knock on door]

1235
01:18:27,880 --> 01:18:30,600
-[door knob rattles]
-[Martín] Ruth. Open the door.

1236
01:18:30,680 --> 01:18:32,080
[knocking]

1237
01:18:32,160 --> 01:18:33,160
Ruth.

1238
01:18:34,160 --> 01:18:35,160
Are you okay?

1239
01:18:35,880 --> 01:18:37,920
Do you want me to call Dr. Velasco?

1240
01:18:39,600 --> 01:18:41,160
[knocking on door]

1241
01:18:42,880 --> 01:18:44,440
[footsteps receding]

1242
01:18:44,520 --> 01:18:46,640
[moody dramatic music continues]

1243
01:19:00,600 --> 01:19:02,600
[suspenseful music playing]

1244
01:19:27,720 --> 01:19:30,600
ALFONSO ALWAYS MAKES US SMILE

1245
01:19:30,680 --> 01:19:31,680
[door closing]

1246
01:19:34,800 --> 01:19:36,080
[car door opening]

1247
01:19:40,160 --> 01:19:41,320
[car door closing]

1248
01:19:44,120 --> 01:19:45,720
[vehicle engine starts]

1249
01:20:02,880 --> 01:20:04,680
CIVIL GUARD

1250
01:20:25,040 --> 01:20:26,760
I'm here to talk to Sergeant Ballester.

1251
01:20:32,240 --> 01:20:33,960
He's not answering. Wait a moment.

1252
01:20:34,040 --> 01:20:36,440
-I can't wait, it's an emergency.
-What? Hey!

1253
01:20:41,720 --> 01:20:42,720
Hey!

1254
01:20:42,800 --> 01:20:44,680
[music continues]

1255
01:20:52,280 --> 01:20:53,480
[guard] Excuse me.

1256
01:20:54,720 --> 01:20:56,160
You can't be back here.

1257
01:20:56,240 --> 01:20:58,240
[dramatic music playing]

1258
01:21:22,600 --> 01:21:24,960
[suspenseful music playing]

1259
01:21:25,040 --> 01:21:26,560
[knob rattling]

1260
01:21:28,120 --> 01:21:31,280
[grunting]

1261
01:21:45,400 --> 01:21:47,200
[grunting]

1262
01:21:48,560 --> 01:21:49,880
Ruth!

1263
01:21:49,960 --> 01:21:51,120
What are you doing?

1264
01:21:52,440 --> 01:21:53,760
What are you doing, Ruth?

1265
01:21:58,520 --> 01:21:59,680
I'm sorry.

1266
01:22:01,200 --> 01:22:02,680
I'm sorry for everything.

1267
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:10,120
Can you make me
one of your herbal teas, please, Dad?

1268
01:22:11,000 --> 01:22:12,120
Of course.

1269
01:22:22,680 --> 01:22:24,040
[music stops]

1270
01:22:24,120 --> 01:22:27,160
[breathing shakily]

1271
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:30,200
[tense foreboding music playing]

1272
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:53,240
[music fades]

1273
01:23:04,280 --> 01:23:05,840
[cell phone buzzing]

1274
01:23:08,520 --> 01:23:10,720
UNKNOWN NUMBER

1275
01:23:17,160 --> 01:23:19,520
[Ballester] <i>Ruth, this is</i>
<i>Sergeant Ballester.</i>

1276
01:23:20,280 --> 01:23:21,880
<i>They told me you came to see me.</i>

1277
01:23:22,480 --> 01:23:23,600
Yeah.

1278
01:23:24,280 --> 01:23:26,720
<i>You probably saw your father in my office.</i>

1279
01:23:27,760 --> 01:23:29,040
<i>I think we need to talk.</i>

1280
01:23:29,120 --> 01:23:30,120
Because?

1281
01:23:30,920 --> 01:23:34,280
<i>Your father came to see me this morning</i>
<i>to tell me that he thinks…</i>

1282
01:23:35,520 --> 01:23:39,120
<i>that you might be complicit</i>
<i>in your mother's death somehow.</i>

1283
01:23:39,200 --> 01:23:41,080
[melancholy music playing]

1284
01:23:41,160 --> 01:23:43,440
<i>He thinks you have ties</i>
<i>to the pharmaceutical company</i>

1285
01:23:43,520 --> 01:23:45,040
<i>that opened a branch in town.</i>

1286
01:23:45,120 --> 01:23:48,600
<i>He thinks you and others in town</i>
<i>are working together on something.</i>

1287
01:23:49,680 --> 01:23:52,840
<i>He thinks coincidences</i>
<i>don't exist. Anyway…</i>

1288
01:23:52,920 --> 01:23:57,000
<i>Things a person with a lot of free time</i>
<i>would say, someone who feels very alone.</i>

1289
01:23:57,080 --> 01:23:58,720
<i>We've been seeing this a lot.</i>

1290
01:23:59,600 --> 01:24:00,680
STILL LOOKING FOR THE BOY

1291
01:24:00,760 --> 01:24:02,160
ARE THEY INVOLVED?

1292
01:24:02,240 --> 01:24:04,520
<i>I just want you to know, it's our opinion,</i>

1293
01:24:04,600 --> 01:24:07,320
<i>and the opinion of anyone</i>
<i>with even half a brain,</i>

1294
01:24:07,400 --> 01:24:10,040
<i>that the case is closed</i>
<i>and there was no crime.</i>

1295
01:24:11,480 --> 01:24:12,680
It was an accident.

1296
01:24:13,440 --> 01:24:17,040
<i>Every piece of evidence points to it</i>
<i>being a tragic accident, yes.</i>

1297
01:24:23,240 --> 01:24:24,600
Okay, then why?

1298
01:24:25,400 --> 01:24:26,560
<i>Why what?</i>

1299
01:24:30,400 --> 01:24:33,040
But then why invent
this whole crazy story?

1300
01:24:34,120 --> 01:24:38,320
[sighs] <i>Because I'm sure</i>
<i>it's very hard to accept</i>

1301
01:24:38,400 --> 01:24:42,080
<i>that you've lost the person you love</i>
<i>in such a meaningless way.</i>

1302
01:24:43,760 --> 01:24:44,840
[dramatic tone plays]

1303
01:24:50,120 --> 01:24:52,120
It's always easier to blame someone else.

1304
01:24:54,680 --> 01:24:57,440
<i>It's hard to deal with that much pain.</i>

1305
01:24:57,520 --> 01:24:59,840
<i>And I think believing all that</i>

1306
01:24:59,920 --> 01:25:03,400
<i>makes your father feel,</i>
<i>well, special, useful.</i>

1307
01:25:11,200 --> 01:25:13,560
<i>But I just wanted to warn you that…</i>

1308
01:25:14,600 --> 01:25:16,280
<i>your father is a true fanatic.</i>

1309
01:25:16,360 --> 01:25:18,080
<i>And a fanatic is…</i>

1310
01:25:19,040 --> 01:25:20,480
<i>incredibly dangerous.</i>

1311
01:25:30,360 --> 01:25:32,160
<i>Be careful with him, please.</i>

1312
01:25:34,200 --> 01:25:35,160
Thank you.

1313
01:25:38,520 --> 01:25:39,800
[phone clicks]

1314
01:25:39,880 --> 01:25:41,000
[music fades]

1315
01:25:43,000 --> 01:25:43,920
[gasps faintly]

1316
01:25:48,960 --> 01:25:49,960
Hey, Dad?

1317
01:25:53,640 --> 01:25:54,680
Dad?

1318
01:25:55,800 --> 01:25:57,040
-I'm sorry.
-Hey, hey!

1319
01:25:57,120 --> 01:25:58,720
-I'm so sorry.
-Stay right there.

1320
01:25:58,800 --> 01:25:59,720
I just wanna talk.

1321
01:25:59,800 --> 01:26:01,920
[Berta] You almost killed him,
for God's sake.

1322
01:26:02,520 --> 01:26:04,800
Let me explain.
It was… it was a mistake. I didn't…

1323
01:26:06,160 --> 01:26:09,160
-Dad.
-Can't you see he's scared of you?

1324
01:26:09,880 --> 01:26:11,000
With good reason.

1325
01:26:12,200 --> 01:26:14,800
-Oh, Dad, come on.
-All right, give me your hands.

1326
01:26:15,880 --> 01:26:18,280
If you wanna talk to your father,
we have to tie your hands.

1327
01:26:18,360 --> 01:26:21,800
-What are you talking about? How…
-We can't risk you attacking him again.

1328
01:26:21,880 --> 01:26:23,400
Come on, please.

1329
01:26:28,600 --> 01:26:30,080
Do what she says, sweetheart.

1330
01:26:40,920 --> 01:26:42,880
[zip tie tightening]

1331
01:26:44,200 --> 01:26:47,320
It's because I was convinced
you had something to do with Mom's death.

1332
01:26:48,520 --> 01:26:50,640
I'm sorry. I'm sorry, Dad.

1333
01:26:50,720 --> 01:26:52,720
I didn't realize. I don't…

1334
01:26:52,800 --> 01:26:54,600
I didn't mean to hurt you, really.

1335
01:26:54,680 --> 01:26:55,680
[sighs]

1336
01:26:57,880 --> 01:26:59,840
What… What are you going to do?

1337
01:26:59,920 --> 01:27:01,760
Are you gonna call the Civil Guard?

1338
01:27:04,240 --> 01:27:05,200
What happens now?

1339
01:27:06,080 --> 01:27:07,840
[Ruth] Ow. Oh, fuck!

1340
01:27:07,920 --> 01:27:09,680
Is this really necessary?

1341
01:27:13,160 --> 01:27:14,200
Come here.

1342
01:27:19,760 --> 01:27:22,320
Your daughter's becoming
a problem for us, Martín.

1343
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:25,840
We have no idea what she saw
when she was in the attic.

1344
01:27:28,120 --> 01:27:29,360
We have to act fast.

1345
01:27:30,240 --> 01:27:33,040
We have to go to the tunnels now
to find the children.

1346
01:27:33,120 --> 01:27:34,800
[vehicle approaching]

1347
01:27:34,880 --> 01:27:37,200
-[vehicle horn honking]
-[gasps faintly]

1348
01:27:37,280 --> 01:27:39,280
[suspenseful music playing]

1349
01:27:41,200 --> 01:27:42,720
[Berta] Who the fuck is that?

1350
01:27:42,800 --> 01:27:45,160
[Martín] The doctor.
He must have come to see Ruth.

1351
01:27:46,120 --> 01:27:48,920
-[Berta] Get him out of here.
-What are you gonna do with that?

1352
01:27:49,680 --> 01:27:51,000
Is that Arón's pass?

1353
01:27:55,600 --> 01:27:57,680
Please, Dad! No. No, Dad!

1354
01:27:58,280 --> 01:28:00,800
-Please, don't leave me here!
-Stay quiet, Jesus Christ.

1355
01:28:00,880 --> 01:28:02,240
-Dad!
-[TV volume increases]

1356
01:28:02,320 --> 01:28:04,200
[yelling] I need help!

1357
01:28:04,280 --> 01:28:05,560
Would you quit that?

1358
01:28:05,640 --> 01:28:07,080
-Dad! Dad! No.
-Be quiet.

1359
01:28:07,160 --> 01:28:09,560
[muffled yelling]

1360
01:28:13,920 --> 01:28:15,560
[woman on TV] <i>Emma, make your guess.</i>

1361
01:28:15,640 --> 01:28:18,960
-[muffled screaming]
-Let's all just relax a little bit, hmm?

1362
01:28:19,920 --> 01:28:21,200
[car engine starts]

1363
01:28:21,280 --> 01:28:24,200
Hey. Calm down, calm down.
It's been dealt with.

1364
01:28:28,440 --> 01:28:29,600
I'll be in the car.

1365
01:28:29,680 --> 01:28:32,120
-[TV continues indistinctly]
-[Ruth whimpers]

1366
01:28:34,080 --> 01:28:35,200
[mutes TV]

1367
01:28:43,680 --> 01:28:44,680
[coughs]

1368
01:28:46,200 --> 01:28:48,720
Dad, what are you
going to do with Arón's key card?

1369
01:28:50,240 --> 01:28:52,280
Did Mom find out what you're working on?

1370
01:28:52,920 --> 01:28:55,240
Is that why you deleted
everything on her phone?

1371
01:28:56,000 --> 01:28:59,880
Your mother went into the attic, as well.
She found out about what we're gonna do.

1372
01:29:00,400 --> 01:29:01,720
And she lost it.

1373
01:29:02,320 --> 01:29:04,480
After that, she started
drinking more than normal.

1374
01:29:04,560 --> 01:29:07,560
But I think her death was no accident.

1375
01:29:07,640 --> 01:29:09,280
Somebody killed her.

1376
01:29:10,920 --> 01:29:13,160
You really believe that
I was involved somehow?

1377
01:29:13,240 --> 01:29:15,880
I know you would never
try to hurt your mother.

1378
01:29:16,480 --> 01:29:18,360
But they could have used you to frame me,

1379
01:29:18,440 --> 01:29:21,280
to implicate me in her death
and get me out of the way.

1380
01:29:21,880 --> 01:29:24,240
I didn't think so at first, but all this,

1381
01:29:24,320 --> 01:29:27,280
your mother's death
so soon after security caught me

1382
01:29:27,360 --> 01:29:29,520
investigating around their main facility.

1383
01:29:30,000 --> 01:29:31,320
Too much of a coincidence.

1384
01:29:32,080 --> 01:29:33,080
Mom fell down.

1385
01:29:33,840 --> 01:29:36,440
I know it's so hard to accept,
but we have no choice.

1386
01:29:37,200 --> 01:29:40,000
What happened was horrible
but it doesn't help to invent stories.

1387
01:29:40,080 --> 01:29:43,160
I told Dr. Velasco you were asleep
and to come back later this afternoon.

1388
01:29:43,720 --> 01:29:44,640
He'll untie you.

1389
01:29:49,640 --> 01:29:50,560
Dad?

1390
01:29:51,360 --> 01:29:52,280
Come back!

1391
01:29:53,040 --> 01:29:54,040
Oh, shit.

1392
01:29:55,440 --> 01:29:56,720
[car door opens]

1393
01:29:57,880 --> 01:29:59,720
[somber music playing]

1394
01:30:06,240 --> 01:30:07,520
[vehicle engine starts]

1395
01:30:11,720 --> 01:30:12,720
Shit.

1396
01:30:18,440 --> 01:30:21,480
[Ruth yelling] Help! Help!

1397
01:30:22,280 --> 01:30:23,320
[grunting]

1398
01:30:29,880 --> 01:30:33,040
ALEJANDRO HUELVA, MISSING.

1399
01:30:33,960 --> 01:30:35,040
[dramatic tone plays]

1400
01:30:40,640 --> 01:30:41,840
He's in the lake.

1401
01:30:43,200 --> 01:30:45,200
[tense music playing]

1402
01:30:48,320 --> 01:30:49,400
[grunting]

1403
01:30:51,440 --> 01:30:53,120
[panting]

1404
01:30:53,200 --> 01:30:54,520
[groaning]

1405
01:31:04,880 --> 01:31:05,840
[grunts]

1406
01:31:10,000 --> 01:31:11,240
[grunting]

1407
01:31:12,080 --> 01:31:13,040
Ah!

1408
01:31:13,960 --> 01:31:15,120
[groaning]

1409
01:31:18,080 --> 01:31:20,080
[tense music continues]

1410
01:31:22,480 --> 01:31:23,440
[phone beeps]

1411
01:31:23,520 --> 01:31:25,240
[line ringing]

1412
01:31:29,240 --> 01:31:30,400
[groaning softly]

1413
01:31:35,960 --> 01:31:37,760
Arón, you have to listen to me.

1414
01:31:38,640 --> 01:31:41,680
<i>I know I've said</i>
<i>a lot of really stupid things lately.</i>

1415
01:31:41,760 --> 01:31:44,120
<i>I know. But I promise</i>
<i>that this is serious.</i>

1416
01:31:44,200 --> 01:31:47,880
<i>My father has your pass and he's going</i>
<i>to use it to get into the building.</i>

1417
01:31:48,680 --> 01:31:50,320
<i>He might already be inside.</i>

1418
01:31:50,400 --> 01:31:52,880
<i>And that's not all.</i>
<i>He has a gun and explosives.</i>

1419
01:31:52,960 --> 01:31:55,400
<i>That woman, the one with him,</i>
<i>she was in the army.</i>

1420
01:31:55,480 --> 01:31:58,400
<i>She knows how to use them.</i>
<i>They're headed to the basement.</i>

1421
01:31:58,480 --> 01:32:01,840
<i>They think that there are children</i>
<i>hidden in secret tunnels or…</i>

1422
01:32:01,920 --> 01:32:03,360
<i>I don't know.</i>

1423
01:32:03,440 --> 01:32:05,680
<i>God knows what</i>
<i>they're willing to do to find them.</i>

1424
01:32:05,760 --> 01:32:06,800
<i>I'm on my way, okay?</i>

1425
01:32:06,880 --> 01:32:09,320
<i>But I might not get there in time.</i>

1426
01:32:09,400 --> 01:32:11,520
<i>I need you to believe me, please, Arón.</i>

1427
01:32:11,600 --> 01:32:12,640
<i>Please.</i>

1428
01:32:12,720 --> 01:32:14,080
[cell phone beeps]

1429
01:32:14,160 --> 01:32:17,080
[Ruth] <i>…and he's going to use it</i>
<i>to get into the building.</i>

1430
01:32:17,160 --> 01:32:18,880
<i>He might already be inside.</i>

1431
01:32:18,960 --> 01:32:21,960
<i>And that's not all.</i>
<i>He has a gun and explosives.</i>

1432
01:32:24,400 --> 01:32:25,400
Careful.

1433
01:32:27,240 --> 01:32:29,320
[intense music playing]

1434
01:32:37,400 --> 01:32:38,640
[Martín] Wait.

1435
01:32:41,080 --> 01:32:42,200
Let's go.

1436
01:32:48,400 --> 01:32:50,760
[alarm blaring]

1437
01:32:53,160 --> 01:32:54,240
I'll go.

1438
01:33:00,280 --> 01:33:02,080
[alarm continues]

1439
01:33:09,480 --> 01:33:10,480
[Arón grunting]

1440
01:33:25,400 --> 01:33:26,480
[Berta] All good.

1441
01:33:27,880 --> 01:33:28,920
Let's go.

1442
01:33:36,360 --> 01:33:38,400
[alarm continues ringing]

1443
01:33:40,600 --> 01:33:42,000
[beeping]

1444
01:33:53,440 --> 01:33:55,200
[man] Hey! Stop, you can't go in!

1445
01:33:55,280 --> 01:33:57,640
My dad's inside. Let me in the building.

1446
01:33:57,720 --> 01:34:00,080
-[loud explosion]
-[people screaming]

1447
01:34:15,440 --> 01:34:18,520
Arón. Hey, hey, are you all right?

1448
01:34:19,600 --> 01:34:20,680
[explosion]

1449
01:34:23,960 --> 01:34:25,440
[explosion]

1450
01:34:25,520 --> 01:34:27,120
[coughing]

1451
01:34:28,360 --> 01:34:30,800
We have to keep looking.
They must be behind the next wall.

1452
01:34:30,880 --> 01:34:32,400
They have to be back there.

1453
01:34:34,160 --> 01:34:35,920
[alarm ringing]

1454
01:34:41,280 --> 01:34:42,600
Dad, wait.

1455
01:34:42,680 --> 01:34:44,720
Ruth. What… what are you doing here?

1456
01:34:44,800 --> 01:34:47,000
-Go home.
-No. No, you have to come with me.

1457
01:34:47,880 --> 01:34:48,880
I can't, sweetheart.

1458
01:34:48,960 --> 01:34:50,320
The boy isn't here.

1459
01:34:50,400 --> 01:34:52,800
Remember when I cut myself
on metal in the lake?

1460
01:34:52,880 --> 01:34:55,000
It was his bike, it was Alejandro's.

1461
01:34:55,080 --> 01:34:58,040
He drowned in there.
He fell in with his bike, I'm sure of it.

1462
01:34:58,880 --> 01:35:01,880
You would say anything if you thought
it would make me leave with you.

1463
01:35:01,960 --> 01:35:05,000
No, Dad, really. If you don't believe me,
we'll go to the police.

1464
01:35:05,080 --> 01:35:07,400
I'm sure they'll find him.
He's in the lake.

1465
01:35:07,480 --> 01:35:10,960
Even if that were true,
it's not just Alejandro.

1466
01:35:11,040 --> 01:35:15,360
It's all the other children too. The kids
they've taken and the kids they will take.

1467
01:35:15,440 --> 01:35:18,320
Don't you see that we can save
them all by exposing the truth?

1468
01:35:18,400 --> 01:35:22,120
I understand, I do,
but you don't need to save anyone.

1469
01:35:22,200 --> 01:35:23,880
You don't need to save any child.

1470
01:35:23,960 --> 01:35:27,080
You don't need to be the one
to change the world or be a hero.

1471
01:35:28,360 --> 01:35:30,200
Isn't it enough to be my dad?

1472
01:35:31,000 --> 01:35:32,480
Because I really do need you.

1473
01:35:34,120 --> 01:35:37,240
Come with me. We'll make another plan,
we'll come back another day.

1474
01:35:37,320 --> 01:35:39,480
Whatever you want.
I'm not leaving you again.

1475
01:35:39,560 --> 01:35:42,280
I'm never leaving your side again,
I swear, Dad, I promise.

1476
01:35:42,360 --> 01:35:44,440
[loud rumbling]

1477
01:35:44,520 --> 01:35:45,560
I love you.

1478
01:35:49,840 --> 01:35:52,440
-Ruth. Let's go!
-No, no! Come back!

1479
01:35:52,520 --> 01:35:55,000
-[Arón] Let's get outta here!
-[Ruth] Dad!

1480
01:35:56,560 --> 01:35:57,960
[loud rumbling]

1481
01:36:04,960 --> 01:36:08,080
-[alarm ringing]
-[coughing]

1482
01:36:11,920 --> 01:36:13,920
[tense music fades]

1483
01:36:14,000 --> 01:36:15,960
[distant siren blaring]

1484
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:20,640
[emotional music playing]

1485
01:36:20,720 --> 01:36:23,080
[sobbing]

1486
01:36:39,960 --> 01:36:41,960
[music continues]

1487
01:36:44,160 --> 01:36:47,400
[man on radio] <i>Today we woke up</i>
<i>to the sad news that Alejandro Huelva,</i>

1488
01:36:47,480 --> 01:36:49,880
<i>the nine-year-old boy</i>
<i>who went missing a month ago,</i>

1489
01:36:49,960 --> 01:36:52,240
<i>has been found dead in Lake Caldas.</i>

1490
01:36:52,320 --> 01:36:54,880
<i>His body was discovered</i>
<i>trapped under debris.</i>

1491
01:36:54,960 --> 01:36:59,320
<i>A tragedy that adds to the deaths last</i>
<i>week of Martín Arce and Berta Martínez,</i>

1492
01:36:59,400 --> 01:37:02,040
<i>who were killed in the explosions</i>
<i>they themselves caused</i>

1493
01:37:02,120 --> 01:37:05,200
<i>at the headquarters</i>
<i>of the pharmaceutical company Certyx.</i>

1494
01:37:05,280 --> 01:37:07,920
<i>Reports indicate that</i>
<i>the Arce and Martinez believed</i>

1495
01:37:08,000 --> 01:37:10,760
<i>there were hidden tunnels</i>
<i>connected to the basement of the building</i>

1496
01:37:10,840 --> 01:37:13,280
<i>where they would find Alejandro</i>
<i>and other missing children,</i>

1497
